<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     01-16 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Continued Reliance on Government Payments Casts Cloud Over US Agriculture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has been upbeat
about the prospects for farmers in 1989, but analysts also point out
there are some troublesome clouds along the horizon.
   For example, USDA economists Greg Hanson and Duane Hacklander say
this year's farm financial outlook is favorable, in large part
because of continued strength in crop and livestock sales.
   In all, gross sales values of commodities are expected to be in
the range of $148 billion to $152 billion, compared with $149
billion predicted for 1988.
   ``The fundamentals that undergird long-term trends in farm income
are strengthening,'' the two economists said in the current issue of
Agricultural Outlook magazine. ``Land markets improved in 1988 and
the farm balance sheet stabilized. Excess commodity stockpiles were
alleviated by the drought.''
   In 1989, they said, costs of farm production items, or inputs,
and commodity market prices will be in better balance.
   But Hanson and Hacklander added in their report that ``three
negative factors cloud the outlook'' for U.S. agriculture:
   _The farm sector will continue to rely heavily on government
payments in 1989, indicating that it has not fully regained a
competitive edge.
   _According to USDA estimates, about 15,000 commercial farms will
be ``financially on the ropes'' because of last year's drought.
About 15 percent to 20 percent of the highly specialized corn and
soybean farms in drought counties are probably under financial
stress.
   _Excess production, which lowers farm commodity prices, can occur
rapidly. The 1988 drought slashed crop production drastically, but
history shows that output often jumps sharply the following year.
   ``The livestock sector made a remarkable rebound in the
mid-1980s,'' the report said. ``Livestock receipts in 1989 are
forecast $10 billion higher than in 1985. But high crop prices
translate into high feed costs that could dampen livestock net
earnings.''
   Government payments to farmers are expected to decline sharply to
a range of $10 billion to $12 billion from about $14 billion in 1988
and $17 billion in 1987. Much of the slide can be linked to the
decline of surplus grain and other products held by the department's
Commodity Credit Corp., or CCC.
   More than a fifth of the direct government payments in 1989 will
be for the Conservation Reserve Program, the long-term plan that
enables farmers to take highly erodible cropland from production for
10 years.
   ``The 1988-89 trend to lower commodity program payments is not
necessarily representative of permanent gains in farm income and
financial health,'' the report said. ``But livestock receipts and
earnings have surged as legislation has reduced CCC (price support)
loan rates for feed grains.''
   Further, the report said, ``the drop in farm debt and land prices
in the mid-1980s and the rapid growth of exports in 1987-88 suggest
that agriculture can now better compete in world markets.''
   As used by the USDA economists, net farm income includes changes
in the value of inventories held by producers and their depreciation
expenses. For 1989, net farm income is forecast at $44 billion to
$48 billion, up by more than 20 percent from last year.
   ``This range assumes a return to near-trend (crop) yields, plus
additional production from 25 million to 30 million more planted
acres,'' the report said.
   In contrast, net cash income is forecast between $48 billion and
$52 billion, down 10 percent to 15 percent from 1988. Net cash
income is the difference between cash expenses and gross cash income
during the year.
   Last year, despite the drought, net cash income held up well
because many farmers had crops in storage from previous years and
were able to sell those at rising prices to offset 1988 production
losses from the drought.
   ``The critical period for many drought-stressed farmers will be
next spring,'' the report said. ``They will have less corn, soybeans
and spring wheat to sell from storage and will face the prospect of
larger planting expenses because of higher input costs and an
increase in planted acreage.''
   Despite government drought aid, cash flow and loan repayment will
be problems for many crop producers in the first half of this year.
   ``In terms of cash flow generated by production, farmers in 1989
will be less well off than in 1988,'' the report said. ``But, in
terms of wealth generated by production (income plus inventory
growth), farmers will be better off.''
</TEXT>
