<FIRST>u a AM-MudslideDeath     01-16 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mudslide Death,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boulder Crushes Car, Kills Woman, Traps Girl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COOS BAY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boulder tumbled down a hillside during a
mudslide and crushed a car on a coastal mountain road Sunday,
killing a woman and trapping a 6-year-old girl in the wreckage for
nearly seven hours.
   The girl was freed shortly before 8 p.m. and was hospitalized in
stable condition with a broken leg, sheriff's department and
hospital officials said. During her ordeal, she was comforted by her
27-year-old father, who was freed from the wreckage earlier in the
day and was not seriously injured, rescue workers said.
   The slide occurred about 1 p.m. 22 miles east of Coos Bay along
the South Fork of the Coos River on a gravel road owned by
Weyerhaeuser Co., authorities said. The slide occurred 9{ miles east
of the company's Dellwood logging terminal.
   The boulder, about 25 feet in diameter, landed directly on top of
the car, said Coast Guard Lt. Bruce Grinnell, who was part of a
helicopter crew that went to the scene of the slide.
   ``There was a bumper sticking out each end of this rock,''
Grinnell said. ``It's amazing anybody survived it.''
   Other rescuers said the girl was trapped in the front seat of a
1955 Chevrolet, a big, boxy car that was one of Detroit's most
durable models.
   ``The little girl was conscious and she was talking to
(rescuers),'' Grinnell said. ``Her only quote was, `It hurts all
over.'''
   Witnesses said the slide was about 80 feet wide and nearly
completely covered the roadway.
   Weyerhaeser Co. officials said there was a report of a smaller
slide on the road about 11 a.m., and a worker was sent to check. The
second, larger slide apparently occurred moments before the worker
arrived.
   The worker found the car crushed by the boulder, heard people
yelling for help and notified authorities by radio, the company said.
</TEXT>
