<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     01-16 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Percentage Of Black Males In Colleges Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minority enrollment in U.S. colleges increased
over the past decade, but the number of black males enrolled
declined.
   Black males also earned the fewest degrees and made the least
progress in number of faculty positions held, the American Council
on Education said Sunday in its seventh annual status report on
Minorities in Higher Education.
   Federal statistics reviewed by the council found total college
enrollment grew from 11 million to 12.5 million from 1976 to 1986,
but black male enrollment fell from 470,000 to 436,000. Black women,
by contrast, held a steady share throughout the period, starting at
5.1 percent and ending at 5.2 percent.
   Asian and Hispanic participation jumped 15 percent and 17 percent
respectively from 1984 to 1986, fueling an 8 percent gain for
minorities as a group, said the report.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Senate Banking Chief Says Plenty Of Blame For Everyone In S&amp;L Flap</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee
says there likely will have to be changes made in the savings and
loan industry because of the crisis that could cost taxpayers more
than $100 billion.
   Sen. Donald Riegle, D-Mich., whose committee will have to deal
with the issue, was not specific Sunday about what changes he has in
mind.
   Riegle, appearing on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' said that while
S&amp;Ls must put their focus on providing home mortgages, it would be
``an enormous shift backwards' to require them to limit their
activities to such mortgages.
   Riegle said the S&amp;L industry's problems are ``a shared
responsibility'' and he blamed not only the industry and its
regulators, but also President Reagan and Congress. ``The regulatory
process broke down,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Defense Chief Says Pentagon Cuts Could Be Devastating</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgoing Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci is
warning that automatic cuts in the Pentagon budget mandated under
the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law would be ``devastating.''
   There has been speculation that if the Bush administration and
Congress fail to reach agreement on reducing the federal budget
deficit, the White House might be willing to accept the automatic
spending cuts.
   ``It would certainly be devastating to the Defense Department.
... Based on preliminary estimates we'd have to take something like
$26 billion out of the Defense Department,'' Carlucci said Sunday on
ABC's ``This Week With David Brinkley.''
   ``Our force structure is down to about the minimum you can get
and still maintain our rotation schedules,'' he said. ``So cuts of
those dimensions would really mean laying up ships, getting rid of
people, taking away ammunition.''
</TEXT>
