<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 0125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Nicaragua Bjt   01-16 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua, Bjt,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega: Government Plans `Pluralistic' Opening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a march by 5,000 opposition
supporters, President Daniel Ortega said the government plans to
give the opposition greater political opportunity and those who
don't want it can ``look for their democracy in Miami.''
   In his Sunday speech, Ortega also said he would propose severe
budget cuts that would require extensive government layoffs.
   Sunday's opposition demonstration, the largest since a July 10
rally in the town of Nandaime that police broke up with tear gas and
beatings, was called to protest the leftist government's economic
management and political repression.
   The peaceful march through Managua's streets was organized by the
Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinating Committee, a coalition of 14
opposition parties and several unions.
   ``We hope to have more demonstrations like this, more unity.
There's no reason we can't run a single candidate for president next
year,'' said Coordinating Committee president Carlos Huembes.
   He claimed the fragmented opposition parties ``are united against
the Sandinista government.''
   Ortega did not refer directly to the demonstration or next year's
scheduled presidential elections in a speech hours later to about
1,000 representatives of pro-Sandinista organizations. But he said
sectors that oppose the government would be given a ``pluralistic''
opportunity.
   He said that those who have been ``dreaming of Yankee
intervention and the defeat of the revolution'' could ``look for
their democracy in Miami and stop enriching themselves in
Nicaragua.''
   It was a sarcastic reference to the thousands of Nicaraguans who
have fled the country in recent months, many to find themselves
homeless in Miami or other parts of the United States.
   Ortega acknowledged that Nicaragua's economic condition is ``very
critical'' and said the state's budget will have to be cut.
   He gave few specifics except to say the police budget would be
protected but that massive layoffs would be required in most
departments. On Dec. 31, Ortega had said he would cut the defense
budget 40 percent.
   No arrests were reported in the opposition march, whose
participants complained about the economy, saying they were not
earning enough to pay for rice, eggs, beer or milk.
   ``Where is the milk? Children are dying of hunger,'' said one
angry construction worker. Like many, he did not want to give his
name for fear of government retaliation.
   Others said that a quart of milk costs about 45 cents, while a
worker earns just 90 cents a day.
   Ortega blames Nicaragua's economic plight on the war against
U.S.-supported Contra rebels, a U.S. economic boycott and the
battering the nation received in October from Hurricane Joan.
   ``They are killing us with hunger but they don't want to blame
themselves,'' an old man wearing a straw hat said of the government.
   He said he was 81 and the only worse time he could remember was
the early 1930s, when Gen. Augusto Sandino was fighting U.S. Marine
occupiers.
   The 3{-hour march began with a Mass in memory of slain newspaper
editor Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, then wended its way almost two miles
to the cemetery where Chamorro is buried.
   ``Everybody's afraid, but people are beginning to lose their
fear. The hunger does it,'' said Alberto Borge.
   Borge said he was a computer technician, a former Sandinista and
a cousin of the powerful Interior Minister, Tomas Borge.
   The government issued a permit for the march, the largest
anti-Sandinista demonstration since the Nandaime rally.
   More than 40 demonstrators and 10 police were reported injured
and more than 30 people arrested when police broke up that protest.
The Sandinistas claimed Washington instigated the demonstration and
expelled U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton.
   Few police officers were visible Sunday. The Nicaraguan baseball
league's all-star game was given a morning start to coincide with
the march and drew 4,000 spectators.
   Chamorro was publisher of the newspaper La Prensa. His Jan. 10,
1978 assassination galvanized opposition to the dictatorship of the
late Anastasio Somoza, who was toppled a year later by the popular
revolution the Sandinistas rode to power.
   La Prensa, now published by one of Chamorro's sons, is the
country's only opposition newspaper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
