<FIRST>r a PM-KingCalendar     01-16 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-King Calendar,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calendar Marks King Holiday As `Nothing Day'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-King Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advertising agency replaced promotional
calendars distributed to 65 McDonald's restaurants because they
mistakenly labeled the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday as ``National
Nothing Day.''
   Officials at John Malmo Advertising blame a clerical error for
the ``National Nothing Day'' notation on Jan. 16 instead of noting
the federal holiday honoring the slain civil rights leader's
birthday, said spokeswoman Cathleen West. King was born on Jan. 15,
1929, but the federal holiday is the third Monday in January.
   ``It certainly was not done intentionally or maliciously. It was
a terrible clerical oversight,'' she said.
   The managers of 65 McDonald's restaurants in Memphis, where King
was assassinated April 4, 1968, received the calendars to help
remind them when sales promotions begin and end.
   ``It was unfortunately a terrible, terrible oversight,'' said Ms.
West, who handles McDonald's account with Malmo. ``It's not
McDonald's fault.''
   The National Nothing Day holiday has been listed on the calendar
in past years as a spoof of special days that salute everything from
pickles to world poetry, she said.
   The error was not noticed until an annoyed McDonald's employee
called to complain. The managers have received corrected calendars,
Ms. West said.
   The day before the mistake was discovered, the company saluted 10
black high school students as ``McDonald's Talented Teens: Black
History Makers of Tomorrow.'' The students received plaques and $200
awards at a banquet featuring black community leaders, said Steve
Lykins, vice president of Century Management, which owns two dozen
McDonald's restaurants in the region.
</TEXT>
