<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 0525EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-KingPapers     01-16 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-King Papers,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coretta Scott King, Boston University Wrangle Over King Papers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-King Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Martin Luther King Jr.'s message of peace and
justice is remembered today, his widow is fighting Boston University
over 83,000 documents left by the slain civil rights leader.
   Coretta Scott King sued her husband's alma mater in December
1987, seeking return of the papers, which include early glimmerings
of his ``I Have a Dream'' speech, a prescribed diet and hate mail.
She insists they belong with the rest of the King archives at the
King Center in Atlanta.
   Boston University, in turn, sued Mrs. King. The private school
claims it is the rightful owner of all King papers, including the
100,000 in Atlanta.
   Efforts at an out-of-court settlement failed, details of which
neither party will disclose. Instead, both sides want a trial to
settle the matter. But they disagree on what issues the trial should
decide. The dispute is now before state Appeals Court Judge
Christopher Armstrong.
   King earned his doctorate in theology at Boston University in
1955. It was there he met his future wife, a music student.
   In 1964, the year he won the Nobel Peace Prize, King wrote to
Boston University that on his death the university would be ``the
repository of my correspondence, manuscripts and other papers.''
   Four years later, he was assassinated in Memphis, Tenn. He would
have been 60 on Sunday.
   The university's collection represents about one-third of King's
documents and correspondence and it was in the school's possession
when he died.
   The collection is mostly sermons that King composed on yellow
legal paper in his thin scrawl and fills 16 file drawers. There are
also letters, many unsigned from strangers, including hate-filled
ones. One of the few scraps of more personal items is an Alabama
doctor's prescription for a strict diet of bread, lean meat,
vegetable, salad and skim milk.
   Mrs. King's lawyers have argued that her late husband's letter to
Boston University isn't binding, being neither a contract nor a
charitable pledge and in violation of laws governing wills. King
left no will.
   Melvin Miller, an attorney representing Boston University, had
little to say about the case, other than that he was talking to
witnesses and taking depositions.
   ``Nothing's happening,'' he said recently.
   In August, Suffolk Superior Court Judge John L. Murphy said Mrs.
King can sue Boston University for the papers but must then explain
why it took her 23 years to seek their return.
   Murphy said the trial must decide whether the two-decade delay is
unfair to Boston University. He also threw out the university's
claim to own all of King's papers.
   In November, Boston University appealed that ruling to Armstrong.
   ``When Judge Armstrong does rule we expect to be moving to have a
trial right away,'' said Mrs. King's attorney, James F. O'Brien.
   Mrs. King's lawsuit also claimed the collection is not properly
displayed or preserved at Boston University. Some of the documents
are on display in the library, but most is stored in a
climate-controlled room.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
