<DOCNO> AP890116-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 0528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Jamaica     01-16 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jamaica,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embattled Prime Minister Announces National Elections Next Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Edward Seaga, who badly
trails socialist opposition leader Michael Manley in opinion polls,
has set Feb. 9 for Jamaica's first contested general election since
1980.
   Seaga, the Reagan administration's closest ally in the Caribbean,
will be seeking an unprecedented third consecutive term.
   On Sunday, the 58-year-old prime minister told a nationally
televised rally in Kingston: ``It is time for us to settle our
future.''
   During the 1980 election, more than 700 people were killed in
street skirmishes during a nine-month campaign. Last August, Seaga
and Manley signed a ``peace treaty'' setting out a code of conduct
for orderly campaigning.
   Seaga said Sunday that he was calling the election to allow the
shortest possible campaign under Jamaican law.
   Business leaders had urged a short campaign to minimize the risk
of unrest at the height of the winter tourist season. The industry,
Jamaica's main foreign currency earner, is still recovering from
Hurricane Gilbert, which battered the island on Sept. 12.
   Manley and his leftist People's National Party boycotted the last
election, in 1983, in a dispute over voter registration. That left
Seaga's center-right Jamaican Labor Party with all 60 seats in
Parliament.
   In a stirring one-hour speech Sunday, Seaga berated Manley's
record, and took credit for restoring political stablity, economic
recovery and international relations.
   Holding out his arms, he told cheering supports, ``In these
hands, your future is safe.''
   As prime minister during the 1970s, the 64-year-old Manley forged
close relations with Cuba, alarming the United States and foreign
investors.
   He has repeatedly called for a new election since his party's
1980 defeat, but Seaga has held out to give his free-enterprise,
export-oriented policies more time to strengthen the nation's
debt-ridden economy. Under Jamaica's parliamentary system, a prime
minister may call an election at any time before the end of his or
her five-year term.
   Seaga came to power with a pledge to pull Jamaica out of deep
economic decline. There have been recent signs of economic
improvement, but critics say his economic restructuring and
austerity measures have neglected social services such as health and
education, and his popularity has faded.
   Opinion polls have put Seaga's party roughly 13 points behind the
opposition for the past two years. Seaga narrowed the gap slightly
shortly after Hurricane Gilbert, but has since fallen back.
   The century's fiercest hurricane caused 45 deaths and an
estimated $1 billion in damage. Seaga has raised $600 million in
disaster relief from abroad, but there been bickering over relief
distribution.
   During his tenure, Seaga has courted Western governments and
international assistance agencies and has been a staunch supporter
of President Reagan. He was the first foreign leader invited to the
White House after Reagan took office in 1981.
   Manley also has served eight years as prime minister, from 1972
until 1980, earning a reputation as an ardent anti-imperialist and
socialist. In recent years, he has projected a more moderate image
and has portrayed Seaga as arrogant and lacking in compassion.
   No prime minister has won more than two consecutive terms since
universal suffrage was introduced in 1944. Jamaica, a nation of 2.3
million people 90 miles south of Cuba, gained independence from
Britain in 1962.
</TEXT>
