<FIRST>r a PM-MudslideDeath     01-16 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mudslide Death,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Dies, 6-Year-Old Rescued After Boulder Crushes Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COOS BAY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 6-year-old girl told rescuers, ``It hurts
all over,'' while she was trapped for 7{ hours in a mudslide that
crushed her family's car and killed her mother, authorities said.
   The family was taking a drive to see the snow when ``the whole
mountain seemed to come down'' on their car, Coos County Sheriff's
Deputy Dave Nelson.
   The child's father, Michael Perry Edwards, 24, was freed from the
wreckage a short time after Sunday afternoon's accident by a search
and rescue team that happened to be on a training exercise in the
area, Nelson said. He was treated for minor injuries.
   Tasha Edwards was taken to Bay Area Hospital on Sunday night
after the rescue on a steep, muddy hillside 100 feet above the
rain-swollen south fork of the Coos River. She was listed as stable
today with a broken leg.
   Her 24-year-old mother, Vera Anne Edwards, was pronounced dead at
the scene.
   The slide occurred about 20 miles east of Coos Bay on a gravel
road owned by Weyerhaeuser Co.
   ``They came to a small slide and as he was driving around the
slide, the whole mountain seemed to come down on top of him,''
Nelson said.
   Edwards attempted to speed through the slide, but was trapped,
then the car was hit by a boulder at least 20 feet in diameter.
   Coast Guard Lt. Bruce Grinnell, who flew to the scene in a
helicopter, said the boulder landed directly on the car, a 1955
Chevrolet.
   ``There was a bumper sticking out each end of this rock,''
Grinnell said. ``It's amazing anybody survived it.
   ``The little girl was conscious and she was talking to
(rescuers). Her only quote was, `It hurts all over.'''
   The girl's mother was in the right front side of the car. The
girl was trapped in the front seat, rescuers said.
   Witnesses said the slide was about 80 feet wide and covered most
of the roadway, which winds along the hillside about 100 feet above
the muddy river.
   Rescuers said blankets had been passed to the girl during her
ordeal. Her father had remained at the scene and talked with her to
try to reassure her.
   She was extricated from the wreckage shortly after 8 p.m.,
officers said.
   Weyerhaeser officials said there was a report of the small slide
on the road about 11 a.m. so a worker was sent to check. The second,
larger slide apparently occurred moments before the worker reached
the scene.
   The worker found the car, heard people yelling for help and
notified authorities by radio.
