<FIRST>r a PM-Pollard-Wife     01-16 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pollard-Wife,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Imprisoned Wife Of Convicted Spy Back In Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anne Henderson-Pollard, the imprisoned wife
of convicted Israeli spy Jonathan Jay Pollard, is back in a prison
hospital, an official said.
   John Powers, a duty officer at the Federal Detention Center in
Danbury, confirmed Sunday that Mrs. Henderson-Pollard had been
transferred to the Federal Medical Center in Rochester, Minn., ``for
further evaluation and medical treatment if it's needed.''
   Powers said he did not know what led to the transfer the medical
center, where chronically ill inmates are kept.
   But her sister-in-law, Carol Pollard, said Mrs. Henderson-Pollard
collapsed in a bathroom at the prison Thursday night and was taken
to Danbury Hospital before the transfer.
   Mrs. Henderson-Pollard has been to the Minnesota hospital, which
is affiliated with the Mayo Clinic, twice before when she was
transferred there from the Lexington, Ky., hospital prison. Mrs.
Henderson-Pollard was transferred to Danbury in September.
   ``She has been maltreated for the past 25 months and this is the
third time they have sent her back,'' Ms. Pollard said Saturday.
``She is in severe pain now because they took all her medications
away.''
   Mrs. Henderson-Pollard is suffering from a digestive tract
disease, Ms. Pollard said. She has lost 60 pounds during the past
two years and now weighs 90 pounds, she said.
   Powers referred questions on Mrs. Henderson-Pollard's medical
treatment to the federal prisons' main office in Washington, where
phone calls went unanswered Sunday.
   Mrs. Henderson-Pollard was sentenced in March 1987 to five years
in prison after pleading guilty to conspiracy to receive embezzled
government property and being an accessory after the fact to
possession of state secrets.
   Her husband, a former Navy intelligence analyst, was sentenced to
life in prison after pleading guilty to selling secrets to Israel.
Pollard was arrested in November 1985 outside the Israeli embassy in
Washington and is jailed in Springfield, Mo.
   In a November interview, Mrs. Henderson-Pollard contended
authorities were ignoring her physical problems but an administrator
said she was receiving proper medical treatment.
   Lawyers for Mrs. Henderson-Pollard last year filed a motion with
the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington asking for a reduction of
her sentence because of deteriorating health.

</TEXT>
