<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths SUB a0473 01-16 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, SUB, a0473,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf of Blake item to include dropped words</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Ernie Blake</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ernie Blake, who served with U.S.
military intelligence during World War II and helped interrogate
captured Nazi leaders Hermann Goering and Albert Speer, died
Saturday. He was 75.
   Blake, who later founded the Taos Ski Valley resort and was
inducted into the U.S. Ski Hall of Fame in Ishpeming, Mich., in
1987, died of double pneumonia at a hospital here.
   Blake was born Ernest Bloch in Germany in March 1913 and grew up
near the Swiss ski resort of St. Moritz. In 1938, he came to the
United States and served in U.S. military intelligence during the
war.
   In Germany, Blake helped interrogate Goering, Speer and others
during the war crimes trials at Nuremberg.
</TEXT>
