<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 0637EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CentralAmericans-Miami     01-16 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Central Americans-Miami,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Seek Federal Aid, Say Shelter is Jammed With Nicaraguans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bad situation got worse for local officials coping
with an already jammed emergency shelter as more Central Americans
poured into the city after a Texas judge lifted a travel ban.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela's ruling effectively allowed
renewed waves of thousands of aliens who cross the U.S.-Mexico
border into Texas to travel elsewhere while their claims for
political asylum are being processed.
   A majority of them were Nicaraguans headed to Miami, where a
large alien population and a reputation for helping immigrants has
resulted in a massive influx, including almost 500 since the judge's
decision a week ago, according to local officials. About 2,000 have
come here during the last two months.
   ``It was a crisis before and the decision by the judge in Texas
was totally unreasonable,'' said Dade County Manager Joaquin Avino.
   The judge blocked enforcement of a government policy intended to
curb the backlog of asylum cases in such cities as Miami and Los
Angeles and reduce aslyum requests from those trying to enter the
country for economic reasons.
   Miami officials were quickly dispatched to Texas to assess the
situation and put out the word: Bobby Maduro Miami Stadium, opened
Dec. 15 as a shelter for homeless immigrants, is full.
   Elba Bustos, 65, arrived in downtown Miami late last week after a
31-hour bus trip from Texas with her granddaughter.
   ``I'm so happy to be here because the situation in Nicaragua is
so bad,'' Ms. Bustos said wearily while waiting for her daughter,
whom she hadn't seen in three years, to pick her up.
   At Miami Stadium, Julio Avendano, who fled Nicaragua more than
two years ago, waited patiently for three cousins to arrive from
Texas. He hailed the Texas judge's decision as humane because
immigrants had been sleeping out in the cold there.
   ``When I came, I had no one,'' he said. ``The first few nights I
slept on the street.''
   Avendano's relatives will be able to stay at his apartment. But a
number of immigrants have no family or jobs here and are counting on
assistance from the city when they're forced to leave the ballpark.
   The stadium was packed with some 280 homeless Nicaraguans at last
count, sleeping in locker rooms and underneath bleachers and eating
donated food in a makeshift dining area set up in a dank corridor.
   ``We're booked to capacity,'' Avino said, ``and unless they have
a private place waiting for them, we can't take care of them.''
   Community leaders, meanwhile, worry that the city is being
overwhelmed at a time when Super Bowl preparations are in full
swing, and some 1,500 reporters were expected for the big game.
   ``I hate to say it, but because of the Super Bowl, people's
energies are focused in another direction now,'' said Tom Ferguson,
president of the Beacon Council, a businessmen's group.
   In Tallahassee, Gov. Bob Martinez has called for help from the
federal government to avert the potential impact of another 1980
Mariel boatlift, which saw some 125,000 Cubans arrive in the United
States.
   Central Americans have historically set their sights on Miami,
with its large Hispanic population and hopes that work permits and
jobs are easier to come by. An estimated 100,000 Nicaraguans have
already settled here and there's potential for another 100,000
immigrants in 1989.
   Still, fewer work authorizations are being issued under a
stricter review process implemented by immigration officials.
   A poster taped inside the stadium read: ``We're honest people who
want work. With permission, we can show you.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
