<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 0827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     01-16 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Factions Clash, Two Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Moslem factions fought with grenades
and machine guns today in the city's southern slums in another
battle for control of Shiite strongholds, killing two people and
wounding five, police said.
   Syrian troops handling security in Beirut's Moslem sectors
arranged a cease-fire late this morning to stem the fighting, the
third clash in 24 hours, police said.
   The two militias have been locked in a power struggle for
leadership of Lebanon's 1 million Shiites, the country's largest
sect, since April. More than 500 people have been killed and 1,500
wounded in the clashes.
   The Syrian-backed Amal militia and the pro-Iranian Hezbollah
battled with rocket-propelled grenades and machine guns for two
hours before dawn today in the Ghobeiri, Shiyah and Bourj
el-Barajneh districts, police said.
   Today's casualties raised the overall toll since Dec. 31, when
the two factions renewed fighting in Beirut and south Lebanon, to at
least 168 killed and 315 wounded.
   The fundamentalist Hezbollah seeks to create an Iranian-style
Islamic republic in Lebanon. The more secular, nationalist Amal
resents Iran's influence in Lebanon and has been fighting to drive
Hezbollah out of Beirut's southern slums and south Lebanon.
</TEXT>
