<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0488 01-16 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Die, Troops Order Midnight Burials</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after graf 4 pvs, ``The high ...'' to UPDATE
with Cabinet minister criticizing army. PICKS UP graf 5 pvs, ``Hospital
...'' DELETES graf 10 pvs to conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops today shot and killed a
17-year-old Palestinian during a clash with youths in the West Bank,
and another teen-ager died of gunshot wounds suffered earlier,
military officials said.
   Troops elsewhere in the occupied lands forced the midnight burial
of two Palestinians slain last week and limited the number of
relatives allowed to attend, an Arab reporter said. The move
apparently was designed to prevent unrest.
   Today's deaths increased to 359 the number of Palestinians who
have died since the uprising in the occupied territories began 13
months ago. Fifteen Israelis have been killed.
   The high rate of casualties _ eight in the past four days _
brought complaints about army policies from Israeli politicians from
the left and right.
   Minister-without-Portfolio Ehud Olmert, a member of the
right-wing Likud bloc who has charge of Arab affairs, said today
every Arab death caused him personal anguish. Both Israel and the
Palestinians are paying a high price for putting down the uprising,
he said on Israel Radio.
   Olmert said he favored tough measures against rioters, but did
not understand the army's policy for opening fire.
   ``I don't think there's a lot of logic or common sense in
shooting after a boy when he's already finished throwing his stone
and is running away,'' he said. ``There must be some judgment and
some restraint.''
   On Sunday, Olmert and Justice Minister Dan Meridor accused
soldiers of having ``too light a finger on the trigger,'' The Nation
and Hadashot newspapers reported.
   Hospital officials identified the Palestinian killed today in
Hebron as Radwan Sbeih. Arab reporters said he was shot in the chest
when youths stoned soldiers and the troops responded with fire.
   A military spokesman, who was not identified according to
regulations, confirmed the death and said another 17-year-old
Palestinian, Ahmed Mustafa of the Khan Yunis camp in the occupied
Gaza Strip, died today after being shot in the head Saturday.
   At least seven youths were wounded today in clashes, including
four from the Hebron area and three in Bureij camp in Gaza, Arab
reporters and hospital officials said. Military sources confirmed
two people were wounded in Hebron, but had no reports of wounded
from Gaza.
   Masked youths ordered Hebron merchants to closed their stores
after the shootings. The youths, activists in the uprising, called
for a three-day strike to mourn those killed.
   Reports of the recent casualties spurred Energy Minister Moshe
Shahal of the Labor Party to demand a report from the army on its
use of plastic bullets. The bullets were introduced to reduce the
fatality rate but critics complain that they are doing the opposite.
   In the Gaza Strip, the army forced families to bury a 12-year-old
girl and a 17-year-old man at midnight and limited the number of
relatives attending to 15, an Arab reporter said. The Arab reporters
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The 12-year-old girl, Hanadi Sultan, died in Tel Hashomer
Hospital near Tel Aviv where she was flown for treatment after being
shot in the head during a Jan. 10 protest. The 17-year-old, Ziad
Ahmed Radwan, was wounded in Rafah Saturday and died Sunday.
</TEXT>
