<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-BritishAirways     01-16 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-British Airways,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Airways Jumbo Jet Lands After Bomb Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb threat forced a British Airways jumbo jet en
route to London with 240 people aboard to make an emergency landing
in northern Japan today, a transportation official said.
   The threat came in a telephone call to the airline's reservation
office in Tokyo at 3:15 p.m., about one hour after Flight 8 had
taken off from Tokyo's Narita airport, said a Transport Ministry
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The official quoted the anonymous caller as saying in Japanese,
``A plastic bomb was planted on board the plane. It is set to
explode at 4 p.m.''
   He said the Boeing 747 was over the Sea of Japan when the threat
came. It landed safely at the New Chitose airport on Japan's
northernmost island of Hokkaido at 5:37 p.m., the official said.
   A Chitose airport official said authorities were searching the
plane but had found no explosives.
   Many airlines operating in Asia have stepped up security
precautions following intelligence reports that an identified Far
Eastern carrier has been targeted for a possible hijack or bomb
attack in January. The intelligence reports followed the bombing of
a Pan Am jetliner Dec. 21 that killed 270 people.
</TEXT>
