<DOCNO> AP890116-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceSting     01-16 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Sting,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Officer Claims Police Abuse in Long Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black police sergeant whose head was
shoved through a window by a white officer says he was conducting a
self-styled ``sting'' operation aimed at uncovering police racism.
   The encounter was secretly recorded by a camera and sound
equipment mounted inside Sgt. Don Jackson's rental car and by other
cameras filming from an unmarked KNBC-TV news van and car following
at a distance.
   Portions of the encounter, which occurred late Saturday night,
were broadcast Sunday by KNBC, and additional excerpts were aired
today on NBC's ``The Today Show.''
   Jackson, 30, is on stress disability leave from his job in nearby
Hawthorne. He insisted that he and driver Jeff Hill, an off-duty
state corrections officer, did nothing illegal to provoke police.
   ``You merely have to be black in the wrong neighborhood, or even
... the right neighborhood,'' Jackson said. ``We were there five
minutes. We had just gotten off the freeway.''
   Jackson, who belongs to a group called the Police Misconduct
Lawyer Referral Service, said he arranged the sting after hearing
reports of racism in Long Beach. He added that it was ``fully in
commemoration of the efforts of Martin Luther King,'' whose 60th
birthday would have been Sunday.
   Jackson and Hill were stopped by Officers Mark Dickey and Mark
Ramsey as they drove on Pacific Coast Highway at Martin Luther King
Boulevard. The officers claimed the 1977 Buick was straddling lanes,
Jackson said.
   ``I was wearing mechanics coveralls and had intentionally smeared
grease on my hands and face to look like I had just crawled out from
under a car,'' Jackson said. ``I looked dirty and I wasn't driving a
nice car, so I guess he (the police officer) figured they could do
whatever they wanted.''
   Segments of the tape showed the car never strayed over the center
line. The tape showed an officer using profanity during a verbal
exchange with Jackson, who initially refused an order to raise his
hands above his head. When he finally did, the tape clearly showed
the white officer ramming Jackson's head through a storefront window.
   A Long Beach police spokesman, Lt. Mike Hill, denied that Dickey,
who needed six stitches for a gash to his hand, pushed Jackson's
head through the storefront. However, Hill said police are
investigating the allegations.
   Long Beach Mayor Ernie Kell said the arresting officer should be
fired if an investigation determines he used excessive force.
   ``We do not want police officers running amok in the city of Long
Beach,'' he said.
   Police booked Jackson for investigation of interfering with
police and challenging a police officer. They set his bail at
$12,000, then reduced it to $250 and finally released him on his own
recognizance more than six hours later.
   Hill was issued a traffic citation at the scene and released.
   Jackson was involved in a controversy last February when he went
to Los Angeles' trendy Westwood Village with a group of black
youths. He was arrested after allegedly refusing an officer's
request to move along.
</TEXT>
