<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Italy     01-16 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Italy,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Prime Minister In Rome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Hussein Musavi of Iran arrived in Rome
today at the start of a five-day European visit that also will take
him to Poland.
   Musavi, on his first foreign trip in several years, is to meet
with Premier Ciriaco De Mita and Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti.
On Tuesday, he will see Pope John Paul II at the Vatican.
   After Rome, Musavi is to travel to Poland to meet with Premier
Mieczyslaw Rakowksi in Warsaw.
   Iran's official Islamic News agency, monitored in Cyprus, said
Musavi was accompanied by four other government ministers and a
member of parliament.
   Italy is among Iran's major trading partners. The Italians buy
Iranian oil and export machinery, chemical and petrochemical goods.
Italian companies also have major development projects in Iran, and
Italy hopes to win contracts to rebuild Iran's oil refinery and
petrochemical industry.
   Iran has been improving economic ties with Poland and other
eastern European countries since Iran and Iraq agreed to a
cease-fire Aug. 20 in their 8-year war.
   Iran is seeking advanced technology and foreign expertise for a
post-war reconstruction program.
   Poland's Budimex company recently won a $15 million contract to
complete a power station in Iran's Khuzestan province. The Soviets
started construction of the plant but abandoned it because of Iraqi
bombing raids.
</TEXT>
