<FIRST>r a PM-ExplosivesCase     01-16 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Explosives Case,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stolen Explosives Came From Same Mine As Earlier Bombs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONGMONT, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities say 300 pounds of plastic
explosives recovered in a raid here were stolen from the same mine
that was the source of stolen explosives used in a series of
Denver-area bombings.
   Investigators did not cite any links between the two cases.
Authorities are trying to determine whether white supremicists are
behind the latest theft, which led to Friday night's raid at a
Longmont motel.
   Five people were arrested in the raid, including Jon Alexander
Kobert of Fort Collins, Colo. Police said Kobert told agents of the
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms that some of the
explosives were going to be used to bomb police departments.
   Boulder County Sheriff's Sgt. George Dunphy said the explosives
have been traced to the John Jay Mine, northwest of Boulder.
   Gates Hartley, the son of the mine's owner, is accused of
stealing more than 100 pounds of explosives in 1987 and using them
to bomb a gas station, several cars and a high school.
   Hartley, a Navy seaman, has been jailed since last week in
Norfolk, Va., pending extradition to Colorado. He faces
investigation on charges of arson and possession of explosives in
connection with the 1987 bombings.
   In the latest case, Kobert, 29, and four other suspects, all
wearing military gear and armed with guns and switchblade knives,
were arrested after attempting to deliver 300 pounds of explosives,
plus 2,000 blasting caps and detonation cords, to undercover agents,
authorities said.
   Four of the suspects were held at the Denver City Jail awaiting
federal charges. They were identified as Kobert; Richard Sanford
Baxter, 51, of Fort Collins; Andrew Wallace Ferguson, 29, of Fort
Collins; and Jeffery Bart Rudolph, 29, of Akron, Colo.
   Evelyn Jean Moschetti, 18, of LaPorte, Colo., is in the Boulder
County Jail for investigation of possession of explosives and
conspiracy.
</TEXT>
