<DOCNO> AP890116-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BishopControversy Bjt   01-16 0907</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bishop Controversy, Bjt,0928</SECOND>
<HEAD>Qualifications of First Woman Bishop Evoke Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A divorced, former public relations executive with neither a
college nor a seminary degree stands on the verge of giving women
entry into a two-millenium tradition dating to Jesus Christ.
   The Rev. Barbara C. Harris, who held the cross when the first
women were ``illegally'' ordained priests in the Episcopal Church in
1974, is expected this week to gain official approval as the first
woman bishop elected by a church that believes in apostolic
succession, or that the leadership of the church can be traced to
the apostles initially commissioned by Christ.
   ``It's far more than an election. It's really an embracing of the
feminine spiritually. And that is going to be a monumental change,''
said the Rev. Eleanor Lee McGee, an assistant professor of pastoral
counseling at Yale Divinity School.
   But while the other branches of the worldwide Anglican Communion
and major ecumenical partners such as the Catholic Church _ which
also believes in apostolic succession _ weigh the consequences of a
woman bishop, the discussion in the United States has focused on the
qualifications of the particular woman involved.
   ``I know many people in the church who believe in the ordination
of women, but who are appalled by this, and feel it does the
movement no good,'' said the Rev. Andrew Mead, rector of the
Episcopal Church of the Advent in Boston.
   The Episcopal Diocese of Massachusetts elected Harris suffragan,
or assistant, bishop in September. Under church law, the election
requires approval from a majority of Standing Committees and the
bishops leading the 118 dioceses in the United States.
   After the committees gave their approval, ballots were sent
earlier this month to the bishops. A majority are expected to
approve her election as early as Wednesday, paving the way for a
consecration already scheduled Feb. 11 in Boston, said the Rev.
James Solheim, a spokesman for the Massachusetts diocese.
   The Episcopal Church approved the ordination of women in 1976,
two years after the ceremony in which ``the Philadephia 11'' were
``ordained'' in the Church of the Advocate, where Harris was
associate rector prior to her election in Boston. Other women have
been candidates for bishop, but Harris was the first to win election.
   Harris, who has declined interviews until she receives official
approval, said in a sermon last year that her election gives ``new
hope ... and new vision to hundreds of thousands'' who have felt
left out of the denomination.
   But her election also drew unusual opposition. Approving locally
elected bishops normally is ``quite perfunctory,'' but at least 30
of the 118 dioceses have already voted against her approval, Solheim
said.
   While her gender assures Harris a place in religious history,
that is only one of many ``firsts'' for her.
   At least three bishops are said to lack a seminary degree, but
Harris appears to be the only bishop without an undergraduate
college degree in any field.
   And in a church struggling to uphold marriage in a nation with
the world's highest divorce rate, she is thought to be the first
bishop elected after a divorce, though bishops have divorced while
in office.
   In the debate over her election in the United States, gender was
noticeably absent.
   Some moderate voices within the church, such as H. Boone Porter
of The Living Church, an independent national church magazine
headquartered in Milwaukee, objected to Harris' lack of a formal
education and full-time parish experience.
   Harris was ordained a priest in Philadelphia in 1980 after a
career in corporate public relations. In addition to her parish
work, she also recently headed the Episcopal Church Publishing Co.,
which produces the liberal church magazine, The Witness. She studied
theology through correspondence courses and with tutors.
   The issue that has troubled people in the pews, some pastors say,
is her divorce. ``Don't we need encouragement by the chief pastor to
stay faithful?'' Mead said his parishioners have asked.
   Others question the validity of the charges raised against Harris.
   ``To put it bluntly, Barbara was different,'' said the Rev. James
Lewis, director of social ministry for the Diocese of North
Carolina, where the Standing Committee twice voted against approving
her election. ``Basically, they were reflecting what we've had in
this church, a basic white gentleman's club.''
   For women who fought the early battles along with Harris to
remove sexual barriers to the priesthood, the arguments being raised
against the pioneer bishop, who is also black, sound all too
familiar.
   ``With racism and sexism, I always expect there is going to be
difficulty, but I'm always surprised in the way it surfaces,'' said
Ms. McGee. ``There would have been issues raised no matter who it
is.''
   The Rev. Patricia Cadwallader took a traditional route to the
Episcopal priesthood, attending Seabury Western Theological Seminary
at Northwestern University. When she went before the Standing
Committee of the Diocese of Ohio seeking ordination, she recalled
one member saying, ``If you were menstruating on the altar, then the
blood would not be only the blood of Christ, it would be your
blood.''
   Now she sees the same thing happening to Harris.
   ``When you don't like someone or don't like something, you grab
at straws,'' said Ms. Cadwallader, who left the Episcopal Church to
become a Presbyterian minister. ``I think they're grabbing at things
not to like about her. I think she's a giant of a woman.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
