<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iraq-Elections     01-16 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iraq-Elections,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 800 Candidates To Run In General Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 800 candidates were expected to
register for Iraq's third national assembly elections scheduled for
March, a government official said Monday.
   The election for the 255-seat assembly originally was scheduled
for Aug. 30 but delayed until March 3 because of the Aug. 20 United
Nations-sponsored cease-fire in the war with Iran.
   In the last two assembly elections, which are held every four
years, members of the ruling Baath Socialist Party ran along with
indepndent candidates. The last election for the Baath-dominated
assembly was in 1984.
   Many independent candidates were elected to the assembly, which
according to Iraq's constitution, shares legislative powers with the
nine-member Revolution Command Council.
   The council, which has veto powers, must ratify the assembly's
draft legislation before it can become law.
   Iraq has an estimated electorate of 7 million people. Everyone
over 18 can vote.
</TEXT>
