<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     01-16 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Rocket Kabul, Killing 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas made their first rocket
attack on Kabul in nearly three weeks Monday, hitting a residential
district with four missiles that killed four people and wounded
nine, officials reported.
   One killed a 15-year-old girl who was walking in a graveyard,
residents of the area said.
   Western diplomats in embassies near the road to the airport said
they heard eight rockets land. It was the first reported attack
since Dec. 27 by Moslem insurgents, who have moved into the hills
around the capital as Soviet soldiers leave Afghanistan to meet a
Feb. 15 deadline.
   An Interior Ministry statement said the rockets hit the Qalyszman
district, a neighborhood where most houses are built of mud. It said
casualties included women and children, but did not elaborate.
   Guerrillas have increased pressure on supply convoys bound for
the capital.
   On Sunday, Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze of the Soviet
Union ended a three-day visit with a pledge of arms supplies to the
government after the remaining 50,000 Soviet soldiers are gone.
   Shevardnadze implied the withdrawal would go ahead as scheduled
and said his government believes the army of President Najib can
cope with the insurgents on its own.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in April
1978 and use border towns and refugee camps in Pakistan, to which
millions of Afghans have fled, as bases and supply points. They are
supported by Pakistan and the United States.
   Soviet soldiers entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and were
estimated to number 115,000 when the withdrawal began May 15 under
an agreement mediated by the United Nations.
   Moscow has insisted that communists have a role in a postwar
government, but the guerrillas refuse and broke off talks with
Kremlin representatives Jan. 6.
   An insurgent news agency in Islamabad, Pakistan, said Monday
guerrillas had overrun two military posts in the border area but
allowed 200 food trucks through to Kabul.
   It said the posts were captured in the past week and put the
guerrillas within three miles of Jalalabad, a government-held city
42 miles from Pakistan.
   There was no independent confirmation of the report, which said
insurgents captured six tanks and 3,000 weapons. Guerrilla sources
claimed 600 Afghan soldiers and militiamen surrendered.
   Guerrillas also claimed to have increased attacks near Kandahar
in the southeast, Herat in the west and in northern provinces on the
Soviet burder.
   Their news agency said about 200 supply trucks were allowed into
Kabul last week to relieve food and fuel shortages. Reports in the
capital, however, said insurgents continued to attack highway
convoys and few supplies were reaching the city.
   Lines for food and fuel begin to form in early morning. Prices
are rising rapidly in Kabul and power blackouts last several hours a
day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890116-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-Atwater-RNC     01-16 0918</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atwater-RNC,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atwater To Bring Tough Style Of Politics To GOP National Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who made the Pledge of Allegiance and
Willie Horton front-burner issues in the 1988 campaign will bring
the same tough style of politics to the Republican National
Committee.
   As Lee Atwater describes it, it's just a matter of making the
committee ``more issue-oriented.''
   Democrats take a less-benign view.
   ``Lee Atwater is probably the most evil man in America,'' said
Democratic Rep. Pat Schroeder of Colorado, shortly after the
election.
   ``If we have to sink to their level to protect democracy and to
break them of sucking eggs then I'm perfectly willing to do it,''
said Texas Democratic Party chairman Bob Slagle the day
President-elect Bush designated Atwater as his choice for Republican
Party chairman.
   In a recent interview, Atwater laughed off the opposition jibes.
   ``They're running around now, it looks to me, saying they're
going to be tougher on me than we ever were,'' he said. ``Maybe,
we'll be the ones complaining the next time.''
   ``I think that's their problem,'' he went on. ``They don't
understand that voters are not concerned with campaign personalities
and campaign tactics.''
   Atwater was Bush's 1988 campaign manager. On Election Day, with
no doubt about the outcome of the race between Bush and Democrat
Michael Dukakis, Bush and Atwater went jogging. During their run,
Bush offered Atwater his backing to succeed Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr.
as party chairman.
   That backing is enough to make the choice unanimous when RNC
members elect their new chairman two days before Bush takes office.
   At 37, Atwater has worked on three presidential campaigns. His
relationship with Bush began in 1973 when Bush was party chairman
and Atwater was national director of College Republicans, a
22-year-old from Newberry College in South Carolina who was wound as
tight as a Mickey Mouse watch.
   The preppy party chairman who grew up in Greenwich, Conn., and
the raspy-voiced country boy from South Carolina hit it off.
   Atwater recalled that back in those days ``I thought to myself
the two things I'd like to do in politics was manage a presidential
campaign one day and be chairman of the party one day.''
   In his temporary office on the 10th floor of the Bush transition
headquarters, Atwater is a study in motion, a leg bouncing up and
down as he outlined his plans to revamp the RNC.
   He said his goals are to sharpen the committee's campaign
capabilities, launch an outreach program to attract more blacks,
Hispanics, Asians and handicapped voters to the GOP, and to promote
the interests of Bush.
   Bush will be the first president who had experience as his
party's chairman. He served under a Republican president _ Richard
M. Nixon _ who regarded the committee as a minor appendage of the
White House.
   That perception is likely to change markedly during the next four
years.
   During the Reagan presidency, it always was clear that the
political direction came from White House aides such as Lyn Nofziger
and Ed Rollins, not the party chairman.
   At one point, when the White House wanted to exercise
extraordinary control over party affairs, Paul Laxalt, the Nevada
senator and a close personal friend of Reagan, was named general
chairman, a post that emphasized the political impotence of
Fahrenkopf.
   No such arrangement seems possible under Atwater whose political
ties to Bush are stronger than those of any White House aide with
the possible exception of chief of staff John Sununu.
   Atwater describes himself as ``a good nuts and bolts
politician,'' and he intends to bring that skill to the RNC.
   ``We've got to target very early and we've got to be somewhat
brutal in our targeting,'' he said, in elections over the next two
years.
   Control of the redrawing of legislative district lines to conform
with the 1990 census is a major goal of both parties and the
Democrats approach that process with a big edge.
   In 28 states, Democrats control both legislative chambers, while
Republicans have total control in only eight. Party control is split
in 13 states, and Nebraska has a unicameral, non-partisan
legislature.
   Of the nation's 50 governors, 28 are Democrats and 22 Republicans.
   Atwater's approach will be to identify congressional and state
legislative districts offering the greatest opportunity for gains
and concentrate RNC resources there.
   ``We have a bigger cadre of people in our party that have
down-to-earth campaign experience,'' he said, and he is recruiting
them to oversee critical areas.
   Outreach to minorities was the other high priority political goal
mentioned by Atwater.
   ``I am convinced affirmative action did work over the last 25
years and we now have a larger black middle class than we've ever
had,'' he said. ``As it continues to grow that's fertile ground for
us, because we are the party of the middle class.''
   But what most politicians in both parties will watch is whether
Atwater brings the same slashing tactics to the RNC that he used so
effectively in the last presidential campaign.
   ``There are clear issues that separate these parties,'' he said
``and I intend to keep those issues in the forefront.''
   Does that mean voters haven't seen the last of Willie Horton, a
convicted murderer who escaped while on furlough and brutalized a
Maryland couple, and the Pledge of Allegiance?
   ``We're not going to go back on furloughs or the pledge,'' he
said, then pausing a moment, ``If we could get away with it, we
would.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
