<FIRST>r a AM-Dukakis-SouthAfrica     01-16 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dukakis-South Africa,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis, On King Day, Announces Ban On Deals With South Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-King Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis said Monday he will order
an end to excutive branch purchases from companies tied to
white-ruled South Africa.
   ``From this point forward, the message will go out loud and clear
from at least one state government that we are not going to do
business with people who do business with that government and that
country,'' Dukakis told a Martin Luther King Day breakfast audience.
   In a speech to about 2,000 activists and community, business and
government officials, Dukakis recalled King said ``whatever affects
one directly affects all indirectly.''
   ``Apartheid is an affront to humanity everywhere and ...
Massachusetts will raise its strong, proud voice for liberty, for
justice, for democracy whenever and wherever we can.''
   Dukakis said he would sign the executive order Friday. At least
four other states _ Michigan, Maryland, Rhode Island and North
Carolina _ have barred state purchases of goods and services from
companies with ties to racially segregated South Africa.
   In 1983, Massachusetts became the first state to pass legislation
divesting its state pension fund holdings in companies operating in
South Africa.
   Since then, members of the legislative black caucus have promoted
a bill that would also end state purchase of goods and services from
companies that deal with the South African government. The bill
passed the House in 1987 and 1988, but died in the Senate.
   While the caucus continues to push for the bill, it also sought
out Dukakis' support for the executive order, said Rep. Byron
Rushing, the bill's prime sponsor.
   ``I'm sorry that we haven't been able to pass the legislation
yet, but I think this is a good step in the right direction,''
Rushing said.
   The executive order isn't as broad as the legislation, affecting
only executive branch purchases. It will not affect the Legislature,
the courts or quasi-public agencies such as the Massachusetts Port
Authority.
   It also is subject to withdrawal by Dukakis' successor in two
years.
   According to the administration, the order will not result in any
significant cost to the commonwealth. However, it could affect about
200 companies nationwide with a total of $21 million in state
purchasing contracts.
   Companies with South African ties that are sole providers of
goods and services would be exempt.
</TEXT>
