<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-King     01-16 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-King,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Sculpture Unveiled at U.S. Embassy Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-King Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Edward Perkins
unveiled a bust of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. on Monday and
suggested South Africa could learn from the civil rights leader's
philosophy of non-violence.
   Perkins, the first black U.S. ambassador to South Africa,
acknowledged important differences between the two countries. ``But
searching for non-violent solutions is probably something worth
thinking about'' in South Africa, he said.
   Perkins joined Zenos Frudakis, the Philadelphia sculptor who made
the bronze bust, in unveiling it under a tent at a Pretoria site
where a new U.S. Embassy is to be built.
   The event coincided with a federal holiday in the United States
honoring King, who was assassinated in 1968. He would have been 60
years old Sunday.
   The 125 onlookers at the bust unveiling included black and white
South Africans prominent in campaigns against apartheid, and a
low-level representative from the South African Ministry of Foreign
Affairs.
   A 30-member choir from the Roman Catholic church of St. Peter
Claver in Mamelodi, a black township near Pretoria, sang several
civil rights hymns. Women in red headscarves and conical hats woven
from grass mingled with dark-suited diplomats.
   One hymn was ``Senatla Martin Luther King.'' Senatla means leader
in the Sotho language.
   Enos Mabuza, chief minister of South Africa's KaNgwane black
homeland, told the gathering there were striking parallels between
the racial separation in South African today and segregation in the
United States during King's lifetime. A major difference, he said,
was that the U.S. Constitution protects individual rights but South
African laws ``protect white privilege and white-minority rule.''
   Mabuza said ``the black people in this country have realized that
the oppressor will never voluntarily give freedom to the oppressed.
The oppressed must demand that freedom.''
   Perkins participated later in a ceremony at the U.S. consulate in
Durban, where representatives of two feuding black political
organizations held hands during the singing of ``We Shall Overcome.''
   Archie Gumede, co-president of the banned United Democratic
Front, held hands with Frank Mdlalose, a member of the Inkatha Zulu
political group and a health minister in the KwaZulu black homeland
government. Supporters of Inkatha and the UDF have been fighting
each other in the Natal province townships for more than 18 months,
resulting in more than 1,000 deaths.
   Standing in the consulate garden overlooking the Indian Ocean,
Perkins read most of King's ``Letter from a Birmingham Jail.''
Blacks in the audience of about 200 murmured sympathetically at
King's description of police assaults on blacks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
