<DOCNO> AP890116-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Rights     01-16 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Rights,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Human Rights Group Says Psychiatric Hospitals Still a Question</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official human rights commission that has helped
free 400 religious prisoners last year has been unable to break a
wall of silence around Soviet psychiatric hospitals, its chairman
said Monday.
   Fyodor Burlatsky, a journalist who heads a Soviet commission
reviewing human rights cases, was praised by foreign counterparts on
the East-West Conference on Human Rights for winning freedom for
nearly every religious prisoner held in a Soviet prison or labor
camp.
   But Burlatsky had to admit that ``despite our exhaustive efforts,
we have failed to receive information on what happened in
psychiatric hospitals in the past or currently.''
   Lacking expertise, his committee helped foreign psychiatrists
visit the hospitals, but they have been unable to draw clear-cut
conclusions, he said.
   Psychiatric hospitals once under the control of security
officials have been transferred to the Ministry of Health, and
managers are being replaced, he said. Still, his committee is taking
issue with two entire categories of mental diagnosis: ``social
delusion'' and ``slow-going schizophrenia.''
   ``I think these two can be found in many members of the public,''
he said dryly.
   Just two hours before Burlatsky spoke at the news conference, an
editor of the unofficial publication Express-Khronika called The
Associated Press to report one of its staff members had been
detained by police and taken to a Moscow mental hospital.
   Vladimir Ryabakon said contributor Vyatislav Dikterov was being
held in psychiatric Hospital No. 1. Dikterov won government
attention in August by writing to the defense minister to refuse
being drafted into the Red Army on religious and political grounds,
Ryabakon said. He said he had no idea what prompted the detention
Monday.
   Last week, the head of the Soviet psychiatrists' society told
Tass, ``There are no patients in mental hospitals in the U.S.S.R.
who are there for political reasons.'' Georgy Morozov's statement
came the day after Moscow dissidents said it was a continuing
problem.
   Overall, the Western leaders of the East-West Conference had
strong praise for their Soviet counterparts.
   Virtually all of the 400 people on a list of prisoners presented
to the Soviets when the East-West Conference was created a year ago
have been freed, said Patrick Cormack, a Conservative member of the
British Parliament. Cormack said he expects similar results on the
list of 30 names he brought to this week's meeting.
   ``We live in a magic time'' of progress on both arms control and
human rights, said Rev. Theodore Hesburgh, president of the
University of Notre Dame. Committee members said hundreds of
thousands of Bibles are entering the Soviet Union unimpeded.
   Rosalynn Carter, wife of former President Jimmy Carter and
co-chairman of the conference with Burlatsky, said she wants to see
the Soviet Union create legal guarantees of human rights, and that
does appear to be happening.
   Mrs. Carter said the East-West conference was unique in that it
began with each participant criticizing his own nation's human
rights situation. She said she pointed to U.S. problems with
homelessness, unemployment and racial discrimination.
   As his three priorities for his own nation, Burlatsky named
religious freedom, first in practice and then in law; legal
protection of human rights; and legalization of unofficial citizens'
groups.
   Burlatsky said he hopes the Soviet Union will pass a law
guaranteeing freedom of relgion this year, but he added that the
first draft has ``a major problem.'' He said it is being written by
bureaucrats with no contribution from religious believers, and
predicted ``dozens, hundreds, thousands of amendments'' before it is
finished.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890116-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-France-Opera     01-16 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Opera,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barenboim Says Mitterrand Must Settle Opera-Bastille Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paris Opera, Act 2: Daniel Barenboim insists that
President Francois Mitterrand decide whether he should be fired as
musical and artistic director by a lord of fashion, who happens to
be the opera's chairman.
   Monday's key scene: The noted conductor tells a news conference,
``It is for him to choose between my presence and that of the
international artistic community I have gathered and the program of
the chief executive of a couture house.
   ``I am unwilling to have a chief executive of a fashion house
tell me who can sing what role, decide if Pierre Boulez is capable
of conducting an orchestra or whether we have the right to invite
Herbert von Karajan.''
   Pierre Berge, chairman of the Opera-Bastille and president of the
Yves Saint-Laurent fashion house, dismissed Barenboim on Friday on
grounds he wanted too much money.
   Barenboim said Monday he had not received official notification
of his dismissal and would continue ``with difficulty'' as musical
and artistic director of the Opera-Bastille, currently under
construction.
   Agence France-Presse, the French news agency, quoted sources
close to Barenboim later as saying a letter from Berges about the
dismissal was hand-delivered to the conductor. It said the letter
was dated Jan. 14, Saturday.
   Berge has said the dispute could delay the first opera production
at the Opera-Bastille, scheduled for Jan. 10, 1990.
   If Barenboim goes, so might Patrice Chereau, director of the
first production, along with musical talent including Boulez, Jessye
Norman, von Karajan and Sir Georg Solti, who have expressed
solidarity with Barenboim and threatened to leave if he does.
   Trouble has been brewing for weeks at the high-tech music
complex. It pits Barenboim, the Argentine-born Israeli conductor and
concert pianist who has led the Orchestre de Paris for 15 years,
against Berge, the financial wizard behind Yves Saint-Laurent's
fashion empire.
   According to Berge, paying Barenboim $1.1 million a year for four
months spent in Paris is unreasonable. He says the opera made a
counteroffer of $628,570 a year for two years, to replace the
original four-year contract, but it was rejected.
   Berge was appointed by the Socialist government, formed last
year. Barenboim received his post from the previous conservative
government.
   The Culture Ministry broke its silence Monday night and issued a
statement supporting Berge. It said his ``mission is to assure that
the objectives set by government authorities since 1982 are
respected: to create a modern, national opera, popular and meeting
the highest artistic demands.''
   It said Berge acted in the context of two guiding principles:
``the independent management of the establishment and respect for
budgetary constraints imposed by public authorities. Berge made
choices that appeared to him to best assure the opening of the
Bastille Opera.''
   Barenboim, 46, told his news conference earlier: ``It is
abhorrent to me to treat a cultural problem as a political problem,
but it has become one.
   ``The contract I signed in July 1987 was under a different
government, but the president is the same, and that's why he's the
only person who can make the choice.
   ``I am unwilling to have a chief executive of a fashion house
tell me who can sing what role, decide if Pierre Boulez is capable
of conducting an orchestra or whether we have the right to invite
Herbert von Karajan.''
   Responding on French television, Berge said he did not want to
involve Mitterrand. ``It would become a political affair,'' he said.
``It is an affair of big bucks.''
   Money, said Barenboim, was not his ``guiding force,'' and he
would willingly take a salary cut of 20 percent. He also said the
contract requires him to be in Paris seven months a year, not four.
   ``These lies and half-truths are unacceptable,'' he declared.
   Another point of contention involves the number of performances
each year.
   An opera house that will cost more than $400 million and is
intended for the widest possible audience should provide 220
performances, says Berge. That's not realistic, says Barenboim.
   ``You cannot possibly expect a new building to start off
functioning like a 50- or 100-year-old institution,'' Barenboim
said, adding that he hoped to get the Opera-Bastille up to
``cruising speed'' in three to five years.
   When it opens, the Opera-Bastille will be the only opera house in
Paris and the ornate old Palais Garnier, the Paris Opera, which will
be reserved for dance.
   Carlos Ott of Canada designed the glassy, boat-shaped structure,
which dominates the Place de la Bastille and is one of several
architectural projects Mitterrand hopes will improve the eastern
part of the city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
