<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Amin     01-16 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amin,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exiled Ugandan Dictator Rejected By Saudi Hosts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Ugandan dictator Idi Amin is
unwelcome at his home-in-exile in Saudi Arabia, Arab diplomatic
sources said Monday.
   ``His nagging desire to recapture power in Kampala has
embarrassed his Saudi hosts and put his African sympathizers on the
spot,'' said a Riyadh-based Arab ambassador, who insisted on
anonymity.
   Amin, 61, slipped out of Saudi Arabia earlier this month and
surfaced Jan. 10 in Zaire on a false passport with one of his sons.
   Uganda's government has demanded his extradition, probably to
appear before a presidential commission investigating atrocities
under previous regimes.
   Amin's wife and 22 of his children still are in the Saudi Red Sea
port of Jidda, but he finally has alienated his hosts by traveling
to Zaire on false documents.
   ``Idi Amin has gone too far this time, stretching the rules of
Saudi hospitality to the limits,'' said the Arab ambassador. ``He
has been quietly looked upon as persona non grata and won't be
allowed to return.''
   Zaire refused to have Amin and sent him to Senegal to catch a
flight to Riyadh. But Saudi officials barred him from boarding the
plane and the Senegalese returned him to Kinshasa, the capital of
Zaire.
   His predicament has drawn no public comment from Saudi officials.
   The master sergeant who became one of Africa's most ruthless
dictators was ousted from his East African nation in April 1979. He
gained political asylum in Saudi Arabia in 1980, after Libyan leader
Col. Moammar Gadhafi refused to harbor him.
   Amin emerged from relative obscurity in 1981 to unveil to The
Associated Press his plans to conquer Uganda. He said he was
grateful to Saudi leaders for accommodating him and his family in a
Jidda villa. The Saudis also gave him a monthly allowance, two cars
and a telephone.
   This was on the understanding he keep a low profile, shun the
press and quit politics. But, according to sources close to Amin,
the dream of retaking power has haunted Amin.
   Amin apparently believed Saudi Arabia would use its oil-generated
clout to reinstate him as president of Uganda.
   Saudi Arabia maintained cordial ties with successive governments
in Uganda, which has known near-constant civil war since its 1962
independence from Britain.
   Amin's frequent outbursts against Ugandan administrations
obviously embarrassed the Saudis.
   ``He abused the telephone, and his monthly bills frequently ran
up to tens of thousands of riyals (dollars), with calls to his
followers in African capitals and press reporters in Arab and
European countries,'' said a Saudi businessman with government
connections. ``When the school in Jidda complained about Amin not
paying his children's school fees, the (Saudi) government hastened
to foot the bills.''
   Two years ago, the Saudis disconnected the telephone.
   Despite Saudi obstruction, Amin would sneak out of his villa for
interviews with Western reporters at downtown hotels.
   He often boasted in interviews of his ``services to Islam'' and
claimed he converted more than 6 million Ugandans to Islam. Only 6
percent of Uganda's 15 million people are Moslems. More than 60
percent are Christians and the rest are animists.
   Some press reports on his eight-year tyranny, during which tens
of thousands of his political opponents and innocent civilians were
killed, alleged the dictator practiced cannibalism. The reports
never were verified.
   ``Do I look like a cannibal?'' he once said in an interview.
``No, I am not. I'm a good Moslem and will live and die a good
Moslem. I'm a poor man without any money.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
