<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Philippine President Hospitalized With Pneumonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
remained in a hospital Monday, suffering from pneumonia and
bronchial asthma, a nursing supervisor said.
   Marcos, 71, has been hospitalized three times in little more than
a month. He was resting in guarded condition Monday at Saint Francis
Medical Center after being admitted Sunday afternoon, according to a
hospital spokeswoman.
   Marcos spokesman Gemmo Trinidad said Marcos was in the intensive
care unit and not allowed to have visitors, except for his wife,
Imelda, and a few close aides.
   ``He's just resting,'' Trinidad said. ``I don't know how he got
pneumonia, but he's very weak and I guess that makes it more likely
for him to get sick.''
   Marcos' doctors, who have been monitoring his condition since he
was last released from the hospital Jan. 5, decided that he should
return, Trinidad said, adding that Marcos would remain hospitalized
at least until Tuesday.
   Marcos' two previous hospital stays, one for nine days and the
other for seven, were for treatment of congestive heart failure, his
doctors said.
   A federal court hearing was scheduled Thursday in New York to
determine if Marcos is healthy enough to travel there for
arraignment on racketeering charges.
   An indictment returned Oct. 21 accused the Marcoses of plundering
more than $100 million from their homeland and using the money to
buy art and real estate in Manhattan. Mrs. Marcos is free on $5
million bail after pleading innocent to the charges in New York.
