<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     01-16 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Koreas Agree to Highest Level of Talks Since War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea on Monday accepted a
proposal from rival South Korea for their prime ministers to lead
the highest level military and political talks since the Korean War.
   ``The north and south should remove the state of tension which is
driving the same people toward disaster and prepare a firm
foundation for peaceful unification,'' North Korean Prime Minister
Yon Hyung Mok said in a letter agreeing to the proposal from Prime
Minister Kang Young-hoon of South Korea.
   Korea's peninsula still faces the threat of war and tension has
to be defused, said the letter.
   It proposed a Feb. 8 meeting of vice ministers at Panmunjom truce
site to work out terms for the talks. No date was mentioned for the
main talks, and the two sides are expected to have problems agreeing
on terms.
   Observers consider a major diplomatic breakthrough unlikely as
long as North Korean leader Kim Il Sung remains in power. Kim
ordered the 1950 North Korean invasion of the south that started the
war.
   Yon's sometimes caustic letter repeated North Korea's call for
separate three-way talks with South Korea and the United States on
reducing tension. The north also demanded an end to annual South
Korean-U.S. ``Team Spirit'' military exercises and accused
Washington of planning a nuclear war.
   ``It is obvious to everyone that the north and south cannot
fundamentally resolve the question of peace by setting aside the
United States, which is the party responsible for the aggravation of
tension,'' the letter said.
   South Korea and the United States have rejected three-way talks,
saying negotiations should be between the two Koreas. The United
States has 42,000 troops based in the south under a mutual defense
treaty against the north.
   South Korean officials have warned that North Korea wants to use
the talks to secure withdrawal of the U.S. forces.
   In his letter Monday, the North Korean premier said the proposed
talks also should focus on halting ``large-scale provocative
military exercises.''
   Talks between legislators from the two sides ran into trouble
last month after the north suddenly demanded an end to South
Korean-U.S. military exercises. The demand came as the two sides
appeared close to agreeing terms for parliamentary talks on a
non-aggression pact.
   Lawmakers are due to meet again next month.
   U.S. and Soviet forces divided the Korean peninsula in 1945 when
they ended Japan's occupation at the end of World War II.
   The two nations have clashed since then and keep hundreds of
thousands of heavily armed troops along the 150-mile border. The
frontier is sealed and there are no communication links except a
single hot line.
   South Korea agreed last month to North Korea's call for
high-level political and military talks and proposed prime ministers
head the delegations to make the discussion the most important since
the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
