<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Burundi 1stLd-Writethru a0528 01-16 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Burundi, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burundi's Ex-President Granted Asylum in Libya</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBVS 1st graf to CORRECT spelling to Jean Baptiste Bagaza,
sted Jean Batista Bagaza.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya has granted political asylum to
former Burundi President Jean Baptiste Bagaza, who was toppled in a
1987 military coup, a newspaper reported Monday.
   Bagaza and his wife left Sunday on a flight to Libya after he
obtained asylum there, according to the government-owned newspaper
New Vision. He had been living in Uganda since shortly after the
bloodless coup that ousted him.
   Military officers, led by Burundi's current president, Maj.
Pierre Buyoya, ousted Bagaza on Sept. 3, 1987, ending his 11-year
rule.
   Bagaza said he should be allowed to return to Burundi because he
has not been found guilty of any wrongdoing, the newspaper reported.
   Burundi, a landlocked East African nation, has been torn by
tribal strife between the ruling Tutsi and the majority Hutu. The
latest major clash came in August, when 5,000 people were killed and
more than 40,000 fled to neighboring Rwanda. Buyoya and Bagaza
belong to the Tutsi tribe.
</TEXT>
