<FIRST>r w AM-Fires-States     01-16 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fires-States,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposal Would Shift Some Firefighting Expense to States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's budget planners have
suggested that states assume some of the cost of fighting fires on
federal lands, a proposal that could cost states millions of dollars
in forfeited revenue from timber and mineral leases.
   It was not immediately clear whether the Bush administration will
adopt the suggestion, which was outlined in the Interior
Department's proposed fiscal l990 budget releases last week.
   The budget calls for the development of a permanent federal
firefighting fund of $166.5 million so that in the years to come the
department will not have to seek extra money from Congress or pay
the bill in subsequent years.
   The department's fiscal 1990 budget, for example, includes a
request for $145 million to pay for part of the firefighting costs
at Yellowstone National Park last year.
   A similar fund would be established in the Agricutlure Department
which funds the Forest Service firefighting programs, officials said.
   The firefighting would be funded from receipts received by the
government from timber and mining activities on federal land.
According to estimates, the firefighting fund would reduce those
total receipts in fiscal l990 by about 18 percent.
   States and local governments share those receipts with the
Interior Department.
   To states and local governments, the establishment of a
firefighting fund would mean a loss of more than $84 million as a
result of a reduction in their share of the mineral and timber
revenues, according to Interior Department estimates.
   The proposal requires congressional approval and is likely to
meet resistance from some western states, whose officials argue that
the federal government should assume the costs of fighting fires on
federal land.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
