<FIRST>r i AM-China-Engagements     01-16 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Engagements,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Childhood Engagements Common in Chinese Countryside</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families in some rural areas of China are finding
marriage partners for children as young as seven and eight, a
newspaper said Monday.
   Childhood engagements in the coastal province of Zhejiang have
resulted in illegal marriages and disrupted efforts to hold down
population growth, according to the overseas edition of the People's
Daily.
   Surveys found that in rural areas around Wenzhou, a city noted
for its prosperous private entrepreneurs, 86 percent of children 14
years old or younger were engaged. Engagements at age seven or eight
were common, the newspaper said.
   In the vicinity of Huzhou, another Zhejiang city near Shanghai,
40 percent of teen-agers had mates picked for them, it said.
   The daily said the young people often begin living with each
other before the legal ages for marriages _ 20 for women and 22 for
men _ creating havoc for birth control programs.
   The arranged marriages, often between families with blood ties,
has led to the birth of disabled children and unhappy pairings
resulting in divorce.
   The Chinese government has discouraged arranged marriages, but
the practice remains common in tradition-bound rural areas. The
official press also has reported that bride selling still is
prevalent in rural areas, particularly in poverty belts where
farmers can earn several years' worth of income by selling a
daughter into marriage.
   The People's Daily urged youth leagues, legal organizations and
family planning offices to educate people that it is wrong to
arrange marriages for children. It said parents who agree to
engagements for their children should be punished and fined.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
