<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1643EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush     01-16 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Pledges Racial Equality Will Mark His Administration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inauguration Roundup Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, who as vice president was part of
an administration criticized for its civil rights record, vowed
Monday to make the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s dream of racial
equality his mission in the White House.
   A day after King's widow, Coretta Scott King, called on Bush to
hold true to his promise of a ``kinder, gentler nation,'' the
president-elect praised the slain civil rights leader as a hero in a
speech to black supporters on the day celebrating King's birth.
   ``He lived a hero's life. He dreamed a hero's dreams. And he left
a hero's indelible mark on the mind and imagination of a great
nation,'' Bush told a breakfast of the American Bicentennial
Presidential Inaugural Afro-American Committee. ``So, today, we
remember the man; we pay tribute to his achievements; and we pledge
once more our nation's sacred honor in continuing pursuit of his
dream.''
   Mrs. King in a Sunday speech at Atlanta's Ebenezer Baptist Church
also urged Bush to impose strict sanctions against South Africa, but
Bush did not mention that subject in his brief remarks.
   Bush retired from public view for the rest of the day,
sequestering himself to work on the inaugural address he will
deliver Friday after he is sworn in as president.
   In statements and meetings with black leaders, Bush has tried to
separate himself from the poor relationship minority groups had with
the Reagan administration, in which he served as vice president for
eight years.
   Lee Atwater, Bush's former campaign manager and the man he chose
to head the Republican National Committee, has a stated goal of
pulling more blacks into the Republican Party. Atwater traveled to
Atlanta to represent the Bush camp at Sunday's King memorial.
   Black leaders have long criticized Reagan as being indifferent to
their cause. Reagan raised the controversy anew in an interview
broadcast Sunday on the CBS television program ``60 Minutes'' by
questioning the motives of some civil rights leaders.
   ``Sometimes I wonder if they really want what they say they want
because some of those leaders are doing very well leading
organizations based on keeping alive the feeling that they're
victims of prejudice,'' Reagan said.
   In 1985, Reagan signed the legislation creating the federal
holiday in honor of King after initially opposing it.
   In his remarks Monday, Bush continued his effort to present his
coming presidency as one that will be sensitive to the concerns of
minorities.
   He called the slain civil rights leader a ``great gift'' from God
to the nation.
   ``What becomes of Martin Luther King's dreams is up to us. We
must not fail him. We must not fail ourselves,'' Bush said. ``And we
must not fail the nation he loved so much and gave his life for. I
understand that _ five days before becoming president of the United
States of America.''
   He recalled the ``moral stain of segregation, the lies it taught,
and the anguish it inflicted on the lives of black Americans and on
the conscience of the entire American people.''
   Bush said King's fight for justice, freedom, peace and equality
will be pursued in years to come, ``that bigotry and indifference to
disadvantage will find no safe home on our shores, in our public
life, in our neighborhoods, or in our home; and that Reverend King's
dream for his children and for ours will be fulfilled.
   ``This must be our mission together. It will, I promise, be my
mission as president of the United States,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Bush transition team sources said Monday that he has
tapped the vice chairman of General Motors Corp., Donald Atwood Jr.,
for the No. 2 job at the Pentagon. A flurry of other appointment
announcements is expected Tuesday.
   Atwood, 63, is the top choice of John Tower, the defense
secretary-designate, to be deputy secretary. The deputy has
responsibility for the Pentagon's daily operation.
   Atwood has filled management positions at GM for 27 years. As
vice chairman, he supervises divisions that manufacture electronics
and airplane systems for the Pentagon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
