<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0600 01-16 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0600,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politicians Express Concern on Casualties; Two More Teens Die</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf, 8th graf ``Israeli newspapers ...'' to recast.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Bullets, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army gunfire killed two more Palestinian
teen-agers Monday and Israeli politicians expressed concern about
the high rate of casualties in the Arab uprising.
   The deaths brought to 10 the number of Palestinian youths killed
in the past five days and raised to 359 the number killed since the
uprising started more than 13 months ago. Fifteen Israelis also have
died.
   Last month, the number of wounded Palestinians reached a record
monthly high of 492 and 26 died, Israel television said. It said the
high casualty figure resulted in part from the army policy of
pursuing each and every rioter.
   In addition, it said, new regulations allowed soldiers to open
plastic or rubber bullet fire at stone-throwers even when they are
fleeing.
   Cabinet Minister Ehud Olmert, a member of the right-wing Likud
bloc, said on Israel radio that soldiers should protect themselves
against Arab stoning attacks, but that army policies were extracting
a ``terrible price'' from Israel.
   Olmert, who is in charge of Arab affairs for the government, said
he favored tough policies against rioters, but added: ``When I get
up in the morning and hear an Arab boy has been killed, I don't get
up with it well. I don't sleep with it well.''
   He called for troops to use ``judgment and restraint'' in putting
down demonstrations.
   Israeli newspapers reported that other ministers discussed army
policy at a Cabinet meeting Sunday.
   Moshe Shahal of the left-leaning Labor Party reportedly demanded
an account on plastic bullets. Israeli troops began using the
ammunition in August in an effort to reduce fatalities, but the
bullets have caused a number of deaths.
   Inquiries at Palestinian hospitals Monday, meanwhile, showed that
four of the 10 most recent deaths were from a new type of rubber
bullet introduced to halt rioting by stone-throwing Arab youths.
   Clashes were reported Monday between troops and stone-throwers in
six spots in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, and officials at Arab
hospitals said 20 people were wounded by army gunfire.
   Hospital officials said one youth was killed and three others
wounded in Hebron on the West Bank. They identified the death youth
as Radwan Abu Sbeih, 17, and said he was shot in the chest.
   Military spokesmen confirmed the death, three injuries in Hebron
and seven other wounds in the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
   The army said another 17-year-old, Ahmed Abu Mustafa, died Monday
of head wounds he suffered two days earlier in a clash at the Khan
Yunis refugee camp in the Gaza Strip.
   According to Arab reports, rioting broke out in the camp Monday
over Mustafa's death, and eight people were wounded when soldiers
opened fire.
   In Hebron, merchants closed their stores after Monday's shootings
when masked youths, organizers in the Palestinian uprising, ordered
a three-day strike to mourn victims of the violence.
   In the Gaza Strip, families guarded by a military patrol buried a
12-year-old girl and a 17-year-old boy just after midnight, an Arab
reporter said. He said the army ordered the midnight burials to
avoid Palestinian protests.
   Both victims were killed by troops in clashes during the past
week.
   Also Monday, an Israeli bus driver suffered minor injuries when
his but was hit by a firebomb in Arab east Jerusalem, police
reported.
   The bus, which was destroyed by fire, was empty except for the
driver. Police said several Arab suspects were arrested.
   Police lifted a four-day curfew on the Arab village of Silwan,
which also is part of east Jerusalem and was annexed by Israel after
the 1967 Middle East war. Army radio said police used the curfew to
round up about 30 Arabs suspected of throwing stones and
participating in violent protests.
</TEXT>
