<DOCNO> AP890116-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 2118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ScienceFront     01-16 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Science Front,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Science Front</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   These are among the developments on the science front reported
Monday:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TYPE A-HEART DISEASE</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Research into the link between Type A
behavior and heart disease suggests that the real killer is anger,
not impatience.
   In a study to be published in Psychosomatic Medicine, researchers
described a followup of 118 students who took a personality test
during law school. Twenty-five years later, 20 percent of those who
had scored in the highest quarter on the hostility scale had died,
compared with 5 percent of those who had scored lowest.
   The research showed that being paranoid or neurotic or avoiding
social contact were not associated with heart attacks. Instead,
those at high risk tend to harbor a cynical mistrust of other
people's motives, get angry often and openly express their
displeasure rather than holding it in.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BALLPLAYERS-TOBACCO CHEW</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-nine percent of a group of
professional baseball players were found to use snuff or chewing
tobacco regularly and nearly half of the users had lesions inside
their mouths, researchers said.
   A 16-person dental team examined ballplayers during spring
training in Arizona last year and found that of those who used
smokeless tobacco at least weekly, 46 percent had oral lesions. Less
than 2 percent of non-tobacco users had such lesions.
   Samples of tissue taken from some of the lesions showed they were
not cancerous, but some are likely to develop into cancer.
   Long-term use of smokeless tobacco, which increases the risk of
cancer of the mouth, also increases the likelihood of high blood
pressure, heart disease, ulcers and cancer of the digestive system.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DISABLED TECHNOLOGY</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dexter the robot hand helps deaf-blind
people listen and a ``talking glove'' lets deaf-mutes speak, but
blind people may find their growing independence threatened by
computer graphics, scientists said Monday.
   A gaze-operated computer keyboard that lets paralyzed people use
their eyes and brain waves to write, talk, move their wheelchairs
and turn on appliances also could be commercially available to the
disabled within a few years, the researchers said.
   Details of several new computerized devices to assist the
disabled were outlined during the annual meeting of the American
Association for the Advancement of Science. So were some problems.
   Lawrence Scadden, director of the Electronic Industries
Foundation's Rehabilitation Engineering Center in Washington, said
that unlike the code used to transmit letters and numbers, the
method by which sophisticated computers ``draw'' pictures, charts
and even text on display screens isn't readily converted into
Braille or a computer's synthesized voice.
   He urged the industry to develop machines to let the blind hear
or feel such information.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>AIDS-PSYCHOIMMUNOLOGY</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Positive thinking, exercise, support from
friends and other ways of reducing stress may help AIDS victims slow
the disease's progression, researchers said.
   According to a new study, blood and psychological tests on 18
AIDS patients found that those who exercised, were assertive and had
lower levels of tension, depression, fatigue, stress and anger also
tended to have higher numbers of disease-fighting immune system
cells.
   Some AIDS researchers cast doubt on the theory, saying that undue
optimism that a positive outlook might slow progression of AIDS
could spur people infected by acquired immune deficiency syndrome to
blame themselves wrongly when their condition worsens.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DESIGNER DRUGS</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Angel dust'' protects the brain during
strokes, heart attacks and surgery, and a safer form of the often
abused street drug could be in wide use soon for some stroke and
cardiac victims, researchers say.
   The drug, known technically as PCP or phencyclidine, acts as a
stimulant and a depressant and produces a psychological state
similar to schizophrenia.
   Dr. Edward F. Domino of the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor
says the potential protective effects of PCP have been found in an
anesthetic called ketamine. PCP and its relatives, including
ketamine, block the chemical changes associated with nerve cell
destruction and thus prevent or limit the loss of nerve cells.
   Ketamine produces the same ill effects as PCP, but they don't
last as long and they can be controlled with certain tranquilizers,
so some version of ketamine might prove to be a safe drug to protect
the brain, Domino said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HEART DISEASE-PROGRESS</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MONTEREY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heart disease remains the nation's
biggest killer, taking a life every 32 seconds, but researchers have
made progress in taming the disease, according to the American Heart
Association.
   Figures released Sunday show that deaths from heart and blood
vessel disease have dropped 24 percent during the past decade.
Researchers attribute the improvement to healthier living habits and
better treatment.
   The association said that in 1986, an estimated 978,500 Americans
died from heart attacks, strokes and other diseases of the heart and
blood vessels. Cancer, the No. 2 killer, took 466,000 lives.
   The association's latest figures show that more than one in four
Americans suffers some form of cardiovascular disease, and almost
half eventually die from it.
</TEXT>
