<FIRST>u a AM-King'sLegacy     01-16 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-King's Legacy,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks Gain Control Of County Government In Landmark Voting Rights
Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-King Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Deans is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few blocks from the bridge where a national
voting rights law was born in bloodshed, three black men took an
oath of office Monday ending 112 years of white political domination
of Dallas County government.
   ``We bring home to Dallas County the harvest of the Martin Luther
King Voting Rights Act,'' said U.S. District Judge U.W. Clemon, the
first black federal judge in Alabama, as he administered the oath of
office to the members of the new Dallas County Commission.
   The three black commissioners _ Erskine Minor, D.L. Pope and
Perry Varner _ were sworn in along with two white commissioners,
Deans Barber and Doug Morrow.
   Until Monday, no black had served on the commission since
Reconstruction. But under a redistricting plan approved after 10
years of legal battles, blacks won control of the five-member
commission in a special election last month.
   Some 300 people sang ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic'' during
the ceremony in a packed county courtroom.
   The ceremony coincided with Alabama's state holiday for both
Confederate Gen. Robert E. Lee and the slain civil rights leader,
who led the 1965 Selma-to-Montgomery voting rights march. The march
took place with federal protection after a band of would-be marchers
were beaten and routed by mounted state troopers on the Edmund
Pettus Bridge, which crosses the Alabama River at Selma.
   ``Bloody Sunday'' drew national attention to the next march led
by King, which helped inspire passage of the 1965 federal Voting
Rights Act.
   ``That act was conceived on the streets of your town. It became a
national commitment on the Edmund Pettus Bridge,'' said James P.
Turner, who investigated the violence in 1965 and is now acting head
of the Justice Department's civil rights division.
   Barber, a white commissioner, said he expected the racially mixed
commission will ``move Selma and Dallas County forward in a
progressive manner.''
   The county, with a population of 55,000, is about 56 percent
black. But blacks had not been able to muster a voting majority due
to low voter turnout during the old, at-large voting system. The
redistricting plan drawn up by the Justice Department created five
districts, two of which have large majorities of blacks.
   ``I suspect there is no place on this planet that is more
identified with Dr. King and his quest for American justice than
right here in Selma, Alabama,'' said Turner at a reception after the
swearing-in. ``I predict that some day students of modern history
will point to Selma, Alabama, as 20th-century America's cradle of
democracy, where people of all races began to live Dr. King's dream
of brotherhood.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
