<FIRST>r a AM-Nunsearch     01-16 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nunsearch,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singing, Dancing Nuns Audition for Part in Hit Musical</HEAD>
<HEAD>By SONNI EFRON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One nun wore sequins. Another, in full Carmelite
habit and veil, sat on center stage and played spoons to a bluegrass
tune.
   Life imitated show business Monday as about a dozen real-life
nuns showed up at the Charles Street Playhouse to audition for a
part in the musical ``Nunsense,'' a gentle spoof of convent life.
   Judging their performances was a panel of nun-impersonators, the
show's regular cast. The actresses sing, clown and even tapdance in
the off-beat comedy about nuns who stage a talent show to raise
money to bury four sisters who died of botulism and are being stored
in the convent freezer.
   Ten nuns had auditioned over the weekend, four of whom were
called back Monday. The five nuns judged most talented will each be
given a cameo role in the show for one week in February or March.
   The show's producers advertised for ``real nuns'' in Catholic and
secular newspapers. They have promised to donate $2 from every
ticket sold for the special shows to a charity chosen by the
performing nun.
   ``We're doing it to raise some money for charity and also of
course to get publicity,''said co-producer Ken Biller.
   ``Nunsense,'' written by Dan Goggin, has played in 30 American
cities since its 1985 debut. It is now playing in Philadelphia, New
York and Boston and has gone on a national tour, said Biller. A
similar, smaller-scale audition for real nuns to appear in the play
was held during its run in Chicago, he said.
   Among the show's biggest fans are the clergy, who applaud its
wacky but respectful humor and pack its performances.
   Several nuns who auditioned said they had dreamed of stage
careers before taking the veil.
   ``I always wanted to go to Hollywood,'' said Sister Marie
Fuhrman, 37, who works with the elderly at the LaBoure Center in
South Boston. ``But I just knew I belonged in the convent.
   ``... Even if I don't make the part, at least I can say I
auditioned for an off-Broadway show,'' she said.
   Sister Rena Foley was a professional dancer who owned her own
dance studio before entering the Sisters of St. Joseph convent at
age 28. Now gray-haired, she donned black stretch pants, a sequined
vest and a top hat for a jazz number complete with shoulder rolls,
high-kicks and splits.
   Also auditioning were two nuns who have performed all over the
world, Sisters Rosalie and Rosemonde Deck, who sing in 14 languages.
   Sister Brigid Riley of the Carmelite Sisters for the Aged and
Infirm in South Boston said she decided to perform her wooden spoon
routine in hopes of attracting more young women to her order.
   She said she believes that nuns' participation in a professional
musical will show young women ``we're not just behind the walls
doing our work. There is joy.''
</TEXT>
