<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0585 01-16 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0585,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Opens Meeting on Reforming Party, Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs UPDATING with quotes, debate adjourned.
Picks up 8th graf pvs, ``The priority...' with minor editing to trim and
conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
hinted of a new stance toward the banned Solidarity labor federation
on Monday, telling a Communist Party meeting that ``all constructive
forces'' should join a campaign for reform.
   The meeting of the 230-member Central Committee is shaping up as
a showdown between hardliners and reformers over restoring legal
status to the trade union movement. Solidarity remains active,
although it was suspended and then outlawed after a December 1981
martial-law decree.
   A government source last week told The Associated Press the
two-day meeting would end with the party offering to legalize
Solidarity under certain conditions, opening the way to broader
talks with the opposition under the leadership of Lech Walesa,
Solidarity's chief and winner of the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize.
   Marian Orzechowski, the party's chief ideologist, told the
five-hour meeting the issue of union pluralism was ``ripe to be
solved'' and said a separate draft position on the topic had been
prepared for a decision by the plenum.
   ``It seems they will register Solidarity,'' said Zbigniew Bujak,
the former underground Solidarity leader, when asked about the
meeting. If so, formal talks between authorities and the opposition
could begin soon, he said.
   But signs of divisions in the party were evident during the
discussion. Nine members spoke, and the debate was to resume Tuesday.
   Official unions chief Alfred Miodowicz told the plenum no
decision on trade unions should be taken until a party conference on
ideology scheduled for early next month, the official PAP news
service reported. Other speakers offered similar sentiments.
   Eryka Gorajek, a forewoman at a northern Poland tire factory,
spoke against legalizing Solidarity. ``Everyone says there should be
only one trade union at an enterprise,'' she said.
   Jaruzelski, whose remarks were broadcast live on state radio, did
not mention Solidarity by name but said political and social life
should be open to different segments of society.
   ``Today we will draw directions of democracy which will include
some pluralistic solutions,'' Jaruzelski said.
   ``The priority goal is radical and irrevocable reconstruction of
social life so that ... there is a place in it for all citizens who
recognize the supreme interests of our country and the unchangeable
shape of its essential framework.'
   By ``supreme interests,'' Poland's leaders usually mean its
membership in the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact military alliance and
maintaining a political system in which the communists have the
leading role.
   The general said the party wants pluralism, but that it should
not be ``confrontational, destructive, anarchic'' if there is to be
any chance ``to unite Poles around a constructive, nationwide
program.''
   Jaruzelski, first secretary of the communist Polish United
Workers Party, alluded to public discontent after a decade of
economic decline and stagnation. People have become ``irritated and
unsure about the future,'' creating problems within the party, he
said.
   ``What does the party expect? What does society expect?''
Jaruzelski asked rhetorically. ``Agreement of all constructive
forces of the nation in the task of reforms and renewal.''
   Referring to the opposition and the party, Jaruzelski said: ``We
are all changing. We are going toward new solutions, aware of the
possible dangers, but hopeful that the others have also drawn
appropriate conclusions about the past years _ that they will
confirm by their actions the care for the country that they profess.
   ``Reconciliation ... is a great opportunity for Poland.''
   Orzechowski, also a Politburo member, said the party has been
re-examining its role recently in a wide-ranging internal discussion.
   ``The problem of trade union pluralism is becoming ripe to be
solved,'' he said.
   But he said any lifting of the ban on allowing more than one
legal trade union should be accompanied by guarantees that there
would be no repeat of the Solidarity era of 1981, when factories
became ``arenas of political struggle.''
   Walesa has demanded that authorities agree to recognize his union
before he will begin talks on Poland's future. Meanwhile, he has
warned that the public's patience is thin after years of rising
prices and consumer shortages, threatening a social explosion that
he might be unable to control.
   Significant opposition to legalizing Solidarity remains,
especially from the leadership of the official trade union alliance
OPZZ, factory-based party organizations, and elements of the army
and police, party sources say.
</TEXT>
