<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Students     01-16 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Students,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Protest Transfer Of Arabs To Separate Dorms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Arab Israeli women stayed in their
dormitory Monday with fellow students who oppose Tel Aviv University
plans to move them away from contact with foreign Jews being
assigned to the dorm.
   The young women and about a dozen supporters refused university
officials' orders to leave, said Yossi Shturm of the Student Union.
He said the union asked a Tel Aviv court Sunday to stop the transfer.
   ``This is a racist decision and it is unacceptable,'' Shturm said.
   Dean of students Gideon Fishelson said the university has moved
nearly 50 students to make room for members of a foreign study
program, and fewer than 10 Arabs were affected.
   But he acknowledged a longstanding university policy of housing
foreign students exclusively with other Jews so they can learn about
Israel and are not influenced by negative Arab ``propaganda.''
   ``We mix them up with Jewish students in order to attain a
Zionist goal, so that after spending one semester here they want to
return to live here afterward,'' Fishelson said by telephone. ``If
one of them asks to live with an Arab student, I won't say no, but
we don't arrange them that way.''
   The women who refused to leave their rooms are citizens from
northern Israel, the dean said.
   In addition to appealing the transfer order, students are
collecting signatures on a petition that says, ``We will not let the
university be dragged into apartheid,'' a reference to South
Africa's policy of racial separation.
   Shturm said the foreign students should be explosed to Israel's
diverse population. ``Students from abroad have to learn to live
with all Israeli students, not just Jews. That's the Israeli
reality.'' he said.
   Arab citizens make up about 17 percent of Israel's 4.2 million
people. They live in Israel proper, not in territories captured in
the 1967 Middle East war.
</TEXT>
