<FIRST>r i AM-Irish     01-16 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Condemns Killing of Reserve Policement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey said Monday
the killing of a reserve policeman was ``brutal and senseless'' and
that his government would spare no effort to find the killers.
   Harry Keyes, 25, was shot on Sunday after he and his girlfriend
left a house in Ballintra, western Ireland, eight miles from the
border with Northern Ireland, police reported. He was the first
victim of Northern Ireland's political and sectarian violence this
year.
   No claim of responsibility was made, but suspicion fell on the
outlawed Irish Republican Army, which is fighting a guerrilla war to
drive the British from Northern Ireland.
   The Republican Press Center in Belfast, through which the IRA
issues its statements, said it had no information about the Keyes
killing.
   Irish police said two gunmen stopped Keyes' car Sunday night as
he was backing out of the driveway, dragged his girlfriend out and
shot the former Royal Ulster Constabulary reserve officer. Police
did not identify the woman, who was not hurt.
   Haughey pledged ``every effort'' to find the gunmen and said in a
statement: ``I strongly condemn the brutal and senseless killing and
extend the deepest sympathies, on behalf of my government, to the
families of those concerned.''
