<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Writers     01-16 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Writers,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writers Meet To Recreate Independent Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 140 writers, unwilling to join a
union created for them by the government, have met to recreate an
independent group dissolved during the 1981 martial law crackdown.
   During the weekend meeting, the writers formed an organizational
committee led by Jan Jozef Szczepanski, a novelist and screenwriter,
who was president of the dissolved Polish Authors Union.
   The writers said in a statement that their decision not to join a
government-sponsored Polish Authors Union shows they place more
value on ``independence and personal dignity than clear advantages''
and that the official group denies them appropriate representation.
   Recreating the group, under the title of the Polish Writers
Society, will help the literary community take part in efforts to
reverse Poland's economic crisis, the writers' statement said.
   The group will continue signing up members and then apply to
authorities for registration as a legal association, a spokesman
said.
   The group also ``welcomed with satisfaction'' the government's
August decision to lift the ban imposed on the Polish P.E.N. Writers
club imposed during martial law, which formally ended in 1983.
</TEXT>
