<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--RhinoPanic     01-16 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Rhino Panic,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rhino Headed To United States Damages Shipping Crate, Causing Traffic
Jam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-bound rhinoceros tried to ram its
way out of it shipping crate Monday, causing a three-hour traffic
jam when the truck carrying it was forced to stop, the United News
of India reported.
   The black African rhino, headed to the airport for shipment to
the Oklahoma City Zoo, panicked and rammed against the walls of the
wooden crate, damaging it and causing the truck to sway to a halt,
the news agency said.
   About 30 police officers directed traffic while 20 Delhi zoo
personnel escorted the 8-year-old black African rhino back to the
zoo after the four-ton animal was tranquilized, the news agency
reported.
   The rhino, born at the zoo, was being sent as part of an animal
exchange program. Cheetahs and a hippopotamus have arrived from the
United States, zoo Director Kamal Naidu told UNI.
   Naidu said the rhino's departure was deferred a week because the
crate was severely damaged.
</TEXT>
