<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-King     01-16 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-King,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Observes `Martinsday'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadians observed Martin Luther King's birthday
with a ``Martinsday'' celebration Monday, a time of tensions between
black community activists and the police.
   The third annual festival for the slain U.S. civil rights
leader's birthday at the small Harbourfront Theater Center included
a forum about police racism.
   On Sunday, about 2,000 metropolitan Toronto police officers met
to protest political pressure they blame for the filing of a
manslaughter charge against an officer who shot a black man.
   The unofficial ``Martinsday'' festival for more than 12 hours
Monday included speeches, music and dance, and discussions about
non-violence and human rights.
   Charles Roach, president of the Martin Luther King Commemoration
Committee, said the late civil rights leader's birthday was marked
in Canada because ``the civil rights and human rights movement was
not confined.''
   ``It was a universal movement,'' he said in a brief interview.
   Canadian police forces still are largely white, but what are
known in Canada as ``visible minorities'' have grown significantly
in urban areas.
   Toronto, whose metropolitan population is 3.5 million, is
especially known for ethnic communities that have increased through
immigration from Asia, Africa, Latin America and the Caribbean.
   Manslaughter charges were filed last week against Constable David
Deviney in the Aug. 9 death of Lester Donaldson at a Toronto rooming
house. Donaldson was one of two blacks killed in police incidents
over a four-month period last year.
   Police protests, including some cases of work stoppages or
refusals to carry weapons, started immediately after the charge was
filed.
   The police who gathered Sunday agreed to stop their protests, but
they demanded Attorney General Ian Scott's resignation. Scott told
reporters later that he wouldn't resign and denied a part in
deciding the criminal charge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
