<FIRST>r a AM-People Sub a0568 01-16 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People, Sub, a0568,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS in London-dateline first item the 4th graf, ``Since The...'
with three grafs to UPDATE with 3 grafs with bootleg albums in West selling
for as much as $885; picks up last graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul McCartney will be ``Back in the U.S.S.R.''
with a new album and a radio call-in show, but without the hit song
from The Beatles' ``White Album.''
   The former Beatle will answer questions from Soviets in a live
phone-in radio program to be broadcast to the Soviet Union on Jan.
26, the British Broadcasting Corp. said Monday.
   McCartney's appearance follows the November release of his new
album. ``Back in the U.S.S.R.,'' produced exclusively for
distribution in the Soviet Union. The album does not contain the
song of the same name recorded by The Beatles.
   Bootleg copies of the album have made it into the West, selling
for $100 to $250 a copy in the United States and for as much as $885
in London, The New York Times reported last week. In the Soviet
Union, the first batch of 50,000 copies sold for 4 rubles each,
about $6.60 at the official rate.
   The owner of a record store in New York's Greenwich Village that
specializes in collectable records said Monday that he sold two of
the albums before the holidays for about $100. The owner, who asked
that his name not be used, said he obtained the records from someone
who was traveling in the Soviet Union.
   McCartney, 46, said in a statement that the record ``was my
response to glasnost, and I'm looking forward to having a chat with
my Russian fans, courtesy of the BBC.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher chatted long-distance to Soviets
last July during a similar program. She took 15 calls on topics from
glasnost to her household chores.
</TEXT>
