<DOCNO> AP890116-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-SettlerState     01-16 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Settler State,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fringe Settler Group Announces Plan for State in Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of ultra-right Jewish settlers announced
Monday they plan to form a new independent Jewish state called Judea
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip if the Israeli government withdraws
from the occupied territories.
   ``We will not allow the heart to be torn from the body of the
land of Israel,'' Michael Ben Horin of the Committee for the
Foundation of the State of Judea told a news conference.
   ``Judea, Samaria and Gaza will always remain Jewish. No Israeli
state will ever be permitted to expel Jews from their homes or their
land,'' the bearded Ben Horin said, referring to the West Bank by
the biblical names Judea and Samaria.
   The West Bank and Gaza Strip were captured by Israel in the 1967
Middle East war, and Palestinians have been rebelling in the
territories for the past 13 months to demand an end to Israeli
occupation.
   Ben Horin and other committee members belong to New York-born
Rabbi Meir Kahane's anti-Arab Kach movement.
   He said the group has some supporters from most settlements in
the territories, but leaders of the mainstream settlement movement
Gush Emunim said they do not back the planned state.
   ``I consider this state to be a joke, so I'm not even going to
waste my time criticizing it,'' said Benny Katzover, a longtime
settler leader who founded the settlement of Elon Moreh near Nablus.
   On Nov. 15, PLO chief Yasser Arafat declared an independent
Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   About 70,000 Jewish settlers live in enclaves among the 1.7
million Palestinians in the two occupied territories.
   Committee member Kutiel Ben Yaakov said Palestinians would be
allowed to remain in the future Judea if they ``agree to sit quietly
there like any other non-Jew.''
   ``But we know they would prefer acts of terrorism against us. My
opinion is there is no room for a hostile population. ... The Arabs
will be allowed to leave peacefully for any other Arab state,'' Ben
Yaakov said.
   Ben Horin said the settler group was putting into place the
infrastructure of the future state in preparation for a possible
Israeli withdrawal from the territories as part of an Arab-Israeli
peace settlement.
   Behind him was displayed a newly designed blue-and-white Judean
flag, which had a star of David embossed with a menorah and a lion's
head and carried the words ``The Lion of Judea Lives.'' The settlers
said the phrase referred to the biblical verse ``You are a lion's
cub, O Judah'' (Gen. 49-9).
   Ben Yaacov said the committee wanted to make its announcement at
the West Bank settlement of Kiryat Arba, but settlement leaders
withdrew permission for such a move under government pressure.
   The announcement was made instead in Jerusalem's Hilton Hotel,
where committee members served cakes and coffee to journalists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
