<DOCNO> AP890116-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 2111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     01-16 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Breaks Up Student Demonstration with Tear Gas; Leftists Call
For Strike</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Students set flaming-tire barricades
and shouted anti-government slogans in Cap Haitien on Monday before
soldiers dispersed hundreds of protesters. Left-wing groups called
for a nationwide strike.
   About 1,000 students at Phillipe Guerrier High School began
protesting after soldiers showed up at the school, apparently
because unidentified agitators threw stones at the building,
reported the Catholic radio station Radio-Soleil.
   ``Down with Avril!'' shouted some of the protesters, referring to
Lt. Gen Prosper Avril, who heads the military government.
   There were no reports of injuries or arrests at the demonstration
in Haiti's second-largest town, north of the capital.
   Also Monday, the Autonomous Union of Haitian Workers and other
left-wing political groups urged business and organizations to honor
a nationwide general strike called for Tuesday.
   The union has accused the Avril government of being indifferent
to the needs of the poor, who are Haiti's majority.
   In another development, the government called for a national
forum next month to discuss creating an electoral council to oversee
presidential elections.
   In a communique released Sunday, the government said the forum
would be held Feb. 9, a date it said was purposely chosen to fall
after Feb. 7 _ the third anniversary of the fall of dictator Jean
Claude Duvalier.
   ``It (the date) would signal a new departure,'' read the
government's release.
   In November the government published a ``draft decree'' calling
for the creation of an electoral council and asked readers'
comments. But the decree was widely criticized as an attempt on the
part of the government to control the electoral process.
   Most political parties agree on the importance of establishing a
dialogue with the government on how to form an electoral council.
But they have set conditions, including the exclusion of former
Duvalier supporters from the forum.
   Many parties say having a new electoral council would be
unconstitutional since the Constitution already provides for an
independent electoral council.
   The constitution, ratified by 99 percent of the voters in a March
1987 referendum, was suspended by then-military ruler Lt. Gen. Henri
Namphy after a massacre at the polls aborted the Nov. 29, 1987
elections.
   Namphy was overthrown in September last year after a coup led by
rank-and-file soldiers put Avril in power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
