<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Arrests,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Sources Say 190 People Detained, Most Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German authorities have released most of the
190 people detained after police used clubs and water cannon to
break up a demonstration by human rights activists in Leipzig,
church sources said Monday.
   About 800 human rights activists gathered at a downtown square in
the southern city Sunday to demand more democracy from the communist
government.
   First reports said about 80 people were detained and taken away
in police trucks when police dispersed the crowd.
   But Lutheran Church sources said Monday that 190 activists were
detained. They said it took hours to determine the exact number.
   Christoph Wonneberger, a priest at St. Luke Church in Leipzig,
said Monday most of those arrested were released.
   He told The Associated Press by telephone that about 400 people
gathered at his church late Sunday to show solidarity with the
arrested activists.
   The Leipzig protesters also demanded the release of 11 dissidents
arrested on Friday and Saturday for distributing leaflets calling
for Sunday's demonstration.
   Wonneberger said nine of the 11 remained in police custody Monday.
   Sunday's protest coincided with official observances of the 70th
anniversary of the murders of Rosa Luxemburg and Karl Liebknecht,
founders of the German Communist Party who were killed by soldiers
during a 1919 uprising.
