<FIRST>u a AM-FurnaceDeaths     01-16 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Furnace Deaths,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Faulty Furnace That Killed Father, Kills Three Relatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB SCHMALFELDT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deadly fumes from a faulty furnace killed a man
last week and then claimed the lives of three relatives who stayed
at his home to plan the funeral but knew nothing of the furnace
problem, authorities said Monday.
   The death last Wednesday of Edward G. Zarnow Sr., 89, at his
suburban Greendale home was originally blamed on a heart attack.
Authorities said they didn't conduct an autopsy last week because
they had no reason to suspect his death was caused by lethal fumes
from the basement furnace.
   Carbon monoxide poisoning caused the deaths Sunday of Zarnow's
son from Australia, his granddaughter and the granddaughter's
husband. A daughter-in-law from Australia was hospitalized in
critical condition.
   Milwaukee County Medical Examiner Jeffrey Jentzen said Monday an
autopsy of the elder Zarnow conducted after his four relatives were
found showed he had a high concentration of the carbon monoxide in
his blood.
   Jentzen identified the relatives as Michael Martin, 38, of
Marshfield, Wis., his wife Karen, 37, and Edward C. Zarnow Jr., 57,
of New South Wales, Australia. Zarnow's wife, Rebecca, 56, also of
Australia, remained in critical condition at St. Luke's Medical
Center in Milwaukee.
   Mrs. Zarnow was being treated in a hyperbaric chamber for carbon
monoxide poisoning, officials said.
   Wisconsin Natural Gas spokesman Paul Markovina said investigators
discovered the gas furnance's regulator was maladjusted, causing too
much gas to go into the furnace.
   The overburning caused incomplete combustion that filled the
house with carbon monoxide, a colorless, odorless and lethal gas,
Markovina said.
   The elder Zarnow suffered from heart and lung disease and
cirrhosis of the liver, causing authorities to assume his death was
by natural causes, Jentzen said.
   ``There was nothing to suggest carbon monoxide death at the
home,'' Jentzen said. ``The sequence of the events, details of the
investigation and examination of the body failed to suggest a carbon
monoxide death.
   ``No medical examiner's office in the country would have done
anything different on this case,'' he added.
   Jentzen said when Zarnow's body was discovered, investigators did
not notice anything suspicious or unusual. He added that none of the
investigators at the scene became ill or complained of the common
symptom of carbon monoxide poisoning.
   Jentzen said if there was any evidence to suggest that the elder
Zarnow had died of carbon monoxide poisoning, an autopsy would have
been conducted immediately.
   Jentzen called the incident ``a very rare and unusual collection
of circumstances.''
   Authorities said the elder Zarnow's relatives were staying at his
home over the weekend while planning his funeral. Sunday morning,
his niece, Audrey Brennan, contacted Greendale police because she
had been unable to reach the four victims on the telephone.
   An officer knocked on the door of the Zarnow house about 10:40
a.m. Sunday but got no response and left the scene.
   At 1:51 p.m., Ms. Brennan again called police, saying she had
gone to the residence and had seen three bodies lying on the floor.
</TEXT>
