<HEAD>57 Tribesmen Arrested For Blocking Logging Roads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-seven Penan tribesmen were
arrested after they set up blockades and prevented logging companies
from felling trees in the jungles on Borneo island, Forestry
Director Leo Chai Liang said Tuesday.
   Leo said the Penans, aged between 20 and 50, were arrested Monday
near Miri on Borneo after they refused to remove trees they used to
block the roads. He said authorities acted following complaints from
two logging companies.
   The arrests brought to 81 the number of the tribesmen taken into
custody this year for blocking logging roads in the rain forests.
All are being held pending trial.
   The Penans, some of whom are nomads, claim logging destroys their
livelihood. There are about 10,000 Penans on the island.
   The government maintains most tribespeople are no longer nomadic
and say logging, plantations and other developments would give them
permanent jobs and fixed incomes.
