<FIRST>r i AM-SudanRebels     01-16 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan Rebels,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khartoum Official Says State Plans New Peace Moves With Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A visiting Sudanese Cabinet minister
said Monday his government plans a new peace initiative with the
southern rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army.
   Mubarak Fadil Mahadi said an agreement signed in September by the
rebels and the Democratic Unionist Party, which quit the government
coalition after officials refused to accept the accord, ``had
positive elements but also some points which have to be developed,
clarified and abrogated.''
   Mahadi, minister for energy, mining, economic and foreign trade,
did not elaborate on his government's proposed move.
   Rebel leader John Garang and Osman Mirghani, leader of the
Democratic Unionist Party, signed the agreement calling for a
cease-fire in southern Sudan, the lifting of a state of emergency
and the convening by Dec. 31 of a constitutional conference attended
by all political parties.
   The Islamic Front Party, another partner in Prime Minister Sadek
Mahdi's government, rejected the accord, which was not binding on
the prime minister. Garang has vowed not to lay down arms until
Sudan's civilian government drops enforcement of Islamic law.
   Traditionally, the country's Moslem majority dominates the
central government. Most of the southerners are Christian or animist.
   The rebels claim to control 90 percent of the southern
countryside and small towns. During the six-year war, a third of the
region's civilian population of 6 million has fled to the north or
to refugee camps in neighboring countries.
