<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 2228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NunLawsuit     01-16 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nun Lawsuit,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Nun May Be Sued for Social Work Malpractice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic nun who pressured an unwed woman
to give up her newborn girl may be sued for social work malpractice,
a state judge ruled.
   State Judge Diane Lebedeff ruled in the state's first such case
that Maureen Dunn could sue Sister Rosalie Gilson of Hicksville and
her Long Island agency, the Catholic Home Bureau for Dependent
Children.
   Ms. Dunn, 30, of Wellesley, Mass., filed a $5 million suit
charging the nun and the agency with ``wrongful deprivation of
custody.''
   The judge, in a ruling issued Friday, denied Ms. Dunn's attempt
to add Cardinal John O'Connor of the New York Archdiocese to the
suit as the effective head of the agency and its employees.
   Ms. Dunn gave birth to a girl on April 6, 1986. Four days later
the child was placed with Mark and Diane Finnican of Hicksville. Ms.
Dunn said she was reassured by Sister Rosalie that she could get the
child back within 30 days if she changed her mind about giving her
up for adoption.
   But Ms. Dunn did not regain custody of the baby until March 1987
when she won a bitter court fight.
   A state appeals court ordered the baby, Kara, returned to Ms.
Dunn after finding that she had signed surrender papers ``under
duress and perhaps even fraud'' in a busy diner on May 1, 1986.
   The court said agency officials did nothing when the Finnicans
refused to return the child after Ms. Dunn said on May 20 that she
wanted her baby back.
   Lebedeff said she found no previous cases of social work
malpractice in New York state.
   But she noted the legislature licenses social workers, and that
under that law, that makes the nun and her agency ``professional.''
The judge said ``practicing one's profession fraudulently,
incompetently or negligently constitutes professional misconduct.''
   In addition, the judge said, there could be a custodial
interference issue because the agency ignored Ms. Dunn's pleas for
return of the baby.
   Custodial interference is a misdemeanor punishable by up to a
year in jail and maximum $1,000 fine.
</TEXT>
