<FIRST>u a AM-NewGuineaQuake     01-16 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Guinea Quake,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Strikes Near Papua New Guinea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake capable of severe damage on Monday
shook an area near the island of New Britain, at the east end of
Papua New Guinea.
   The tremor measuring 6.5 on the Richter scale struck at 2:35 p.m.
HST (7:35 EST) Monday, according to the Pacific Tsunami Warning
Center in Honolulu.
   No Pacific-wide tsunami was generated by the earthquake, the
center reported.
   The temblor was centered near the town of Kandrian on New
Britain's south coast.
   New Britain lies off the northeast coast of mainland Papua New
Guinea.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage. A magnitude
7 quake is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy
damage.
</TEXT>
