<FIRST>r a AM-RussianBond     01-16 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Russian Bond,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Trying to Collect on Russian Bond</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Hampshire hopes its $10,000 in bonds
bought in 1905 from the Soviet Union finally will be a good
investment.
   Officials say chances of getting the Soviets to pay the
long-standing debt have improved thanks to a thaw in U.S.-Soviet
relations and the Soviets' need to borrow Western capital.
   The state bought $10,000 in bonds issued by the czarist
government, as part of the celebration of the end of the
Russo-Japanese War. The treaty that ended the war was negotiated in
Portsmouth.
   When the Communists threw the czar out in 1917 and set up their
own government, they stopped paying the czar's debts.
   Secretary of State William Gardner, who will ask the State
Department to press the state's claim, estimates that with interest,
the state is owed about a half-million dollars.
   The Boston Sunday Globe reported that negotiations are under way
to repay the debts, spurred in part by the Soviet Union's need to
expand its economy. A U.S. law says the country can't lend the
Soviet Union any money until its U.S. debts are paid.
   Gardner said if the Soviets won't pay the claim, the state might
be able to make some money by selling the bonds.
   ``Collectors tell me they are valuable,'' he said.
</TEXT>
