<FIRST>r a AM-HonestyCampaign     01-16 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honesty Campaign,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Panel Headed By Watergate Conspirator Launches Honesty Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A citywide ethics panel headed by a figure
in the Watergate conspiracy this week kicks off an eight-month
campaign to promote honesty.
   ``It's a natural first issue to deal with because of the armored
car incident,'' the Rev. Jeb Stuart Magruder said, referring to a
1987 incident in which motorists stopped their cars to scoop up
hundreds of thousands of dollars of cash that had fallen from an
armored truck onto a busy Columbus freeway.
   Magruder, now executive minister at First Community Church in
suburban Marble Cliff, was chosen last year by Mayor Dana G.
Rinehart as the first chairman of the Columbus Commission on Ethics
and Values.
   Magruder, the former deputy director of communications in the
Nixon White House and deputy director of Nixon's Committee to
Re-elect the President in 1972, served seven months in a federal
prison after he admitted destroying records and committing perjury
in the Watergate coverup attempt.
   Ceremonies set for Wednesday will begin the $75,000 campaign,
called ``Take an Honest Look.'' The committee will plaster its
message on billboards and provide public service ads featuring the
campaign's theme song. Schools, churches and businesses are also to
take part in the effort.
   The project calls for a television show featuring an ``honesty
test,'' an honesty week and having honesty awards, producing
leaflets and coffee mugs, pen sets and other business items with
messages about honesty and urging pastors to preach sermons about
being truthful.
   ``We are simply trying to raise people's consciousness,''
Magruder said.
   Had he been more conscious of ethics and values, Magruder said he
might not have become involved in the Watergate conspiracy.
   ``If Nixon had called us all in and said, `We're not going to
have anything done in this administration that's illegal or
unethical,' it probably would not have happened.''
   ``I think it's a characteristic in American life that there is
redemption,'' Magruder said.
</TEXT>
