<FIRST>u a AM-NoahRobinson 1stLd-Writethru a0624 01-16 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Noah Robinson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0624,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Starts in Murder Trial of Jesse Jackson's Half-Brother</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf, `Jury selection...' to UPDATE with three jurors
selected; picks up 3rd graf, `He also...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BENJY HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Monday denied a request to
move the murder trial of Noah Robinson, the half-brother of Jesse
Jackson, but said he would reconsider the motion if prospective
jurors appear biased by pre-trial publicity.
   Jury selection began in the trial of Robinson, a Chicago
businessman who is accused of hiring members of Chicago's El Rukn
street gang to kill Leroy ``Hambone'' Barber, a former employee and
a childhood friend of Robinson's in Greenville. Three jurors were
selected Monday.
   He also is accused of conspiring to murder Janice Denise
Rosemond, a witness to the slaying who later survived a brutal
stabbing attack. Five El Rukn members also are charged. Their cases
are being handled separately.
   Albert Taylor Jr., an attorney for Robinson, had asked the trial
be moved to Charleston because of the publicity surrounding the case.
   He entered as evidence a tape of news reports by WYFF-TV in
Greenville and said The Greenville News and the Greenville Piedmont
had published 137 stories on the case since November 1987.
   He said it was ``inconceivable'' that any prospective juror did
not hear or read the news reports.
   Taylor also accused Solicitor Joe Watson of releasing evidence to
the media in an attempt to influence prospective jurors.
   Watson denied the charge. ``I have done everything I could to
keep down pre-trial publicity,'' he told Circuit Judge James Moore.
   Watson said Robinson and his attorneys contributed to the
publicity because they had sent numerous releases to the media.
   Moore gave no reason for his decision to deny the motion. He
said, however, that he would be willing to reconsider the motion
during jury selection if it appears that the publicity has damaged
Robinson's chance for a fair trial.
   Jury selection could take several days to complete, officials
said.
   The judge dismissed on Monday candidates who were related to
anyone involved in the case, medically unable to be a participant,
over 65 and unwilling to serve or already decided about the guilt or
innocence of Robinson.
   After cutting the number of prospective jurors from about 150 to
112 Monday afternoon, the judge divided them into four groups of 28
people each. People in the first group were questioned by attorneys
Monday and officials were to call the remaining groups.
   When a jury is selected, that person would be taken home, allowed
to pack and then sequestered, officials said.
   About 50 people watched the proceedings in the Greenville County
Courthouse. All spectators had to pass through a metal detector
before they could enter the third-floor courtroom.
   Robinson has maintained that he is a victim of a political
conspiracy caused partly by the success of his half-brother.
Robinson and Jackson share the same father, but the former
Democratic presidential hopeful has said he has had no recent
contact with his half-brother.
   Barber was shot in the head on Jan. 2, 1986, while standing in a
phone booth inside a Greenville shopping center owned by Robinson.
   In a brief arraignment held last week in Greenville, Robinson
pleaded innocent to the Barber slaying. He was jailed for about 10
weeks after his September arrest until a judge agreed to let him
post $1 million bond.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
