<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Wolves Adv27-29   01-16 0918</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Wolves, Adv 27-29,0947</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Jan 27-29 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: The Passion of Photography</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One breath on the viewfinder of his camera as
he photographed a pack of six Arctic wolves taught Jim Brandenburg
the difficulties of shooting in frigid temperatures when excited.
   The warm, moist air coated the viewfinder glass with a layer of
ice.
   ``This must be scraped off with your fingernail, which means
removing your two sets of gloves, which means freezing your
fingers,'' Brandenburg recounts in his book, ``White Wolf: Living
With an Arctic Legend.''
   The 160-page book, which evolved from a May 1987 ``National
Geographic'' cover story, recounts in words and photographs the
summer of 1986 when Brandenburg and biologist L. David Mech lived
among a pack of wild white wolves on Ellesmere Island, 500 miles
from the North Pole.
   Brandenburg first spotted the arctic wolf pack while
photographing the historic dogsled journey to the North Pole led by
Will Steger. He persuaded National Geographic to let him do a story
on Ellesmere Island and asked Mech, who has devoted the past 30
years to the scientific study of wolves, to accompany him.
   Mech also wrote a book about the experience, ``The Arctic Wolf:
Living With the Pack,'' after deciding against collaborating with
Brandenburg on a single book.
   Photographs included in Brandenburg's book have won many
prestigious awards, including Magazine Picture Story of the Year,
and first and second place in the nature category from the National
Press Photographers Association; first place in the nature category
from the World Press Photography contest; and the No. 1 cover for
1987 in a National Geographic Survey.
   He also was named 1988 Wildlife Photographer of the Year by BBC
Wildlife Magazine and Kodak for his white wolf photographs.
   Brandenburg, 43, a Minnesota native who began working as a
contract photographer for National Geographic Society after working
as a photographer for the Worthington Daily Globe, had been
photographing wolves in their natural habitat for 20 years before
going to Ellesmere Island. He had photographed wolves in Canada,
Alaska, northern Minnesota, China and the Soviet Union.
   But it's the Ellesmere Island experience that stands out. ``This
story was the most important story I've ever done. This is the
highlight of my career,'' Brandenburg said.
   Although there were hardships _ temperatures ranged from 70
degrees below zero to 70 degrees above zero and Brandenburg
destroyed the cartilege in his knees kneeling on the ice _ those
aren't the things that stand out in his memory.
   ``I don't remember one difficult day. I just remember a positive
dream. It was wonderful all the way through,'' Brandenburg said.
``Their tolerance of me up there is probably the most profound
feeling I have.''
   When Brandenburg returned to the island last spring to do some
followup work for the book, he crawled into the wolf den to
photograph pups, a first in nature photography.
   ``I had spent so much time that they weren't concerned with my
proximity to the pups,'' he said. ``I was more concerned about my
intruding into what was an intimate bedroom. I wouldn't have done it
if I thought there would be a problem.''
   The mother of the pups came back into the den a few minutes after
Brandenburg left, he said, and the animals resumed their routines.
   ``Sometimes I forget I'm actually working for a living with this.
I don't think of it as a business. It's sort of a passion. I can't
stop doing it.''
   The book, with a first printing of 50,000 copies and a second
printing planned, is the culmination of that passion.
   ``There is something about a book that is really precious,'' he
said. ``It's a cultural thing. It's almost like giving birth to a
child.''
   Craftsmanship isn't the only reason Brandenburg takes pride in
the book.
   ``I think the book is making a difference in people's attitudes
toward nature and especially toward wolves,'' he said. ``Even if it
makes 10 people change their ideas about wolves, it's worth it to
me. Those rewards are greater than the financial ones.''
   Brandenburg, who studied art in college and has never taken a
photography course, said he considers it important that his
photographs are both accurate and artistic.
   He tries to present work that will attract people who normally
aren't interested in science or the environment: ``I feel with the
environmental problems we have, we are going to have to get into
people's hearts rather than their heads.''
   A small, gentle man with haunting pale blue eyes, Brandenburg
speaks of nature with quiet reverence.
   ``My God is what I see and what I breathe and what I feel,'' he
said. ``I know we have something here _ a certain kind of heaven _
that we are despoiling. And that's a sin. I think we should live in
harmony with the environment.''
   In keeping with that philosophy, he is donating some of the
profits from his book to wolf education and environmental education.
Some of the proceeds are going to the Wolf Ridge Environmental
Learning Center on Lake Superior's North Shore and the environmental
group Defenders of Wildlife.
   He is also organizing a benefit concert for wolves which will
feature musicians Paul Winter and James Taylor.
   ``That is the most satisfying thing of all _ trying to change
people's attitudes toward creatures I love and respect,''
Brandenburg said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Jan 27-29</NOTE>
