<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Jan 27-29 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Loverboy Guitarist Goes It Alone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the early 1980s, Loverboy dominated radio with
such hits as ``Turn Me Loose'' and ``Working for the Weekend.''
   Although their mainstream power-pop music wasn't popular with
critics _ ``corporate rock'' it was called _ millions of fans played
Loverboy's records. Loud.
   According to guitarist Paul Dean, however, the group then went
``soft'' in 1984 when lead singer Mike Reno made a duet with Heart's
Ann Wilson on the ballad ``Almost Paradise,'' a smash hit from the
soundtrack of ``Footloose.''
   Loverboy had been regarded as just another faceless band, but
suddenly Reno's trademark headband made him famous around the world.
The rest of the group, meanwhile, remained largely unknown.
Dissension set in. Now, Dean says, ``we're not communicating that
great.''
   ```Almost Paradise' made Mike a ton of dough for five hours
work,'' Dean said. ``We went from being a high energy rock band to
being a ballad band. People just got ideas. Our record company would
come up to us and say, `Look what `Journey' did with ballads.'''
   On ``Hard Core,'' Dean's first solo album, the guitarist
dispenses with Loverboy's keyboard sound and delivers nine songs
that are sure to test the most expensive speaker systems.
   ``I was being buried by a keyboard player and production team,''
Dean said of his later work with Loverboy.
   Dean put together his own band for ``Hard Core.'' From Loverboy
came drummer Matt Burnette, a longtime friend; Geraldo Domenelli
helps out on guitars and Dave Watson, who played bass for country
star Lee Greenwood, rounds out the group.
   ``I started rehearsing a trio while mixing the last Loverboy
album,'' Dean said. ``I was not involved in the production of that
album. I was in a $35 an hour studio, rehearsing and making demos.''
   Also chipping in are some hard core rock 'n' rollers: fellow
Canadian Bryan Adams, KISS member Paul Stanley, and Jon Bon Jovi,
who plays harp on the Adams composition, ``Draw the Line.''
   Stanley wrote the album's first single, ``Sword to Stone,'' a
song Dean originally meant to record with Loverboy.
   ``I played it for the guys in the band and they laughed and said,
`Get serious.' There are a lot of things that Mike can't stand. He
wants to sing good time stuff. I guess he felt it was too heavy
metal.''
   Dean's own roots are a combination of country and rock. He was
born in 1946 in British Columbia and recalled listening to a country
music station from Spokane, Wash., on radio at night.
   Johnny Cash was an early hero, but so were the Ventures, an
instrumental group in the early '60s best known for ``Walk, Don't
Run.''
   ``I wore out that record,'' he said. ``I had quarters on the tone
arm, trying to get it to play one more time. I had the first 10
Venture albums and learned all the parts. I drove my parents mad,
but that's the idea, isn't it?
   He didn't fare much better with employers. After attending the
University of British Columbia, he tried holding a job during the
day and playing in bands at night. It didn't last very long.
   ``I worked with the Coca-Cola company as a deliverer for a week.
I was sleeping on the job because I was playing bars until 3,'' Dean
recalled. ``I also had jobs in warehouses. ... I was good for maybe
a month or two, but I just couldn't handle it.''
   Even playing full time, Dean's career made little progress until
1978 when he met Reno in Calgary and the two decided to put a band
together. ``I was tired of working with front men and putting all my
energy behind then and getting screwed in the end,'' he said.
   Dean came up with the name for the group in 1979: ``I was looking
through some magazines sitting on the table, `Glamour' and `Cosmo,'
just sitting on the table. There were cover girls everywhere and I
thought `Coverboy,' then `Loverboy.'''
   Their self-titled debut album came out in the fall of 1980 and
went platinum in the United States and Canada. With the release of
``Get Lucky'' in 1981, and the smash hit, ``Working for the
Weekend,'' Loverboy established itself as one of the world's hottest
bands.
   ``It was like a magic plan that worked,'' Dean said. ``I had been
in so many bands and thought this is how it should work. I was
always one thing short. When it all finally happened I was really
impressed.''
   In 1983, Loverboy released ``Keep It Up,'' another platinum
seller which yielded the hit singles ``Hot Girls in Love'' and
``Queen of the Broken Hearts.'' ``Lovin' Every Minute of It,'' which
came out in 1985, had three more hits, but by the time ``Notorious''
was released two years later, the thrill was gone.
   ``I felt I wanted to keep the band together,'' Dean said. ``But
the tunes on `Notorious' were not the best.''
   So the days of filling arenas with screaming fans are over for
now. Dean is back to playing clubs again, hoping to build an
audience for his solo record.
   ``I don't think they're waiting in line with baited breath. I
don't think anyone even knows about the record, to be honest. Not
many people are even aware that the band is taking a break from each
other.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Jan 27-29</NOTE>
