<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--LaserSurgery Adv19   01-16 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Laser Surgery, Adv 19,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Jan. 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Debate Over Methods Increases With Popularity Of Laser Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Vijay Maker operates in a hospital, his laser
a ``magic knife'' that seals off blood vessels, kills bacteria and
reduces pain.
   Dr. Philip Morris, who works in an outpatient surgery center,
uses a laser to remove cancer from breasts, and sends patients home
hours later with ``so little pain that they only take one or two
little pain pills.''
   The two are among a growing number of doctors who strongly
advocate using lasers _ focused beams of light of a single color, or
wavelength _ for surgery. They also illustrate a growing debate over
what type of laser is best.
   Maker, chief of surgery at Grant Hospital in Chicago, uses a
laser called a YAG, short for yttrium aluminum garnet. Its beam
prevents tissue from bleeding by heat-sealing cells as they are cut.
   The beam can travel through a flexible cord, and in Maker's model
of choice, a pen-like instrument directs the beam through
crystalline tips that touch the surgical surface. That means, he
says, that surgeons who learned to respond to feedback from scalpel
touching tissue make an easy transition.
   Morris, at The Surgery Center in Santa Rosa, Calif., uses a
carbon dioxide laser, which heats a thin layer of tissue until cells
actually explode, or disintegrate. It also seals off small blood
vessels.
   Maker says a carbon dioxide laser, where the beam travels only in
straight lines and must be turned by mirrors, and where the beam
touches skin but the instrument tip has no contact with the tissue,
is far less accurate.
   ``You're shooting pretty much like target practice,'' he said.
``It's a very crude way of doing a very fine surgery like
mastectomy.''
   Morris disagrees, though he admits that a YAG is ``much more
precise.''
   He said a YAG beam, which reacts with red substances like blood,
is better for coagulation, but the beam can penetrate ``deeper than
what you can see ... so the next day a guy might blow a hole out of
his stomach or colon.''
   The wavelength of a CO2 laser makes it heat water, and cells are
90 percent water, he said. But even as one cell is disintegrated by
the beam, ``you don't hurt the tissue right next door.''
   Dr. Leonard Cerullo, an associate professor of surgery at
Northwestern University School of Medicine and director of the
Chicago Neurosurgical Center at Columbus Hospital, said, ``You
really have to match the instrument to the surgical need. I think
it's a mistake to say one size fits all.''
   Despite difference over types of lasers, Maker and Morris agree
that laser surgery in many ways tops traditional methods of
operating.
   Dr. Ellet Drake, secretary of the American Society for Laser
Medicine and Surgery in Wausau, Wis., estimates that more than a
million surgical procedures were done in the past year with lasers,
but he doesn't envision the scalpel being replaced in the forseeable
future.
   Lasers should be used, said Drake, a cardiologist, when ``they
either do something better or do it exclusively. Why use a $100,000
apparatus when you can get by with a $10 apparatus.''
   Albert Einstein first conceived the laser more than 50 years ago,
but it was 1960 before a usable one was built, Drake said.
   Ophthhalmologists were the first doctors to use them widely, and
about 90 percent in that field use lasers to treat ailments
including detached retinas, glaucoma, retinitis and some cataracts,
he said. Most opthamologists use argon lasers, which are lower in
energy than YAG or CO2 models, and the beams can pass through clear
eye tissue to heat the blood-rich retina.
   He said that lasers also are becoming more popular with
obstetricians and gynecologists, with applications from dissolving
venereal warts to breaking up blockages in fallopian tubes. In
dermatology, lasers have proven to be the best tools to lighten
port-wine stain birthmarks. In cardiology, lasers on the ends of
flexible tubes can clear blockages from arteries. And urologists can
use them to break up kidney stones or cut out cancer from bladders.
   Dr. Francis L`Esperance, an opthamologist at
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in New York City, says a new
laser could be used to reshape the retina and eliminate the need for
corrective eyeglasses or contact lenses.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Jan. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
