<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--What'sNew-AtomSmasher Adv19   01-16 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--What's New-Atom Smasher, Adv 19,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Jan. 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>FermiLab's Cancer-Therapy Accelerator Reaches Milestone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATAVIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory
lost out in the battle to house the world's largest atom smasher,
but developed what officials say is the world's smallest _ to
bombard cancer.
   ``It's the first accelerator built exclusively for medical
treatment,'' FermiLab spokeswoman Barbara Lach said of the $60
million cyclotron being built here for the Loma Linda University
Medical Center in California.
   With conventional radiation _ X-rays and gamma rays _ the beams
go right through the patient, said Loma Linda spokesman Dick
Schaefer. ``We're losing 100,000 people in the United States alone
because we can't put enough radiation on the tumor without doing too
much damage to the good tissue.''
   Proton beams, however, ``come through good tissue at a tremendous
rate of speed and come to a stop'' at the directed target, Schaefer
said. The Loma Linda accelerator will deliver 250 million electron
volts.
   Proton therapy and neutron therapy so far available only through
hospitals with access to major physics laboratories. Neutron
therapy, provided since 1976 to patients at Fermilab's Neutron
Therapy Facility, is available at a handful of U.S. hospitals, said
Fermilab physicist Arlene Lennox. ``We've had people from India ...
the Philippines'' and all 50 states for treatment, she said.
   ``There has been talk of running it 24 hours a day because of the
expected interest,'' said Schaefer. Loma Linda is expected to take
delivery this summer.
   ``It's been an international effort to benefit mankind,'' he
said. Researchers from Sweden, Switzerland, Japan, the Soviet Union
and various parts of the United States contributed to the project.
   The facility carried an initial pricetag of $40 million, since
augmented by $20 million from the U.S. Energy Department, Ms. Lennox
said.
   At 50 tons, it really is small only in accelerator terms.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Jan. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
