<DOCNO> AP890116-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 0719EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights TwoTakes   01-16 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, Two Takes,0530</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rate of increase in wholesale prices nearly
doubled in 1988 to 4 percent, the worst pace since Americans began
recovering from double-digit inflation at the beginning of the
decade, the government says.
   Although inflation is still a far cry from 1979 and 1980, when
wholesale prices posted back-to-back increases of 13 percent and 12
percent, many economists said Friday they are worried about the
trend.
   The rise in the Labor Department's Producer Price Index for
finished goods, one stop short of the retail level, was the worst
since 1981, when it shot up 7.1 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales grew in 1988 at their strongest
pace in four years, the government reported, but the year went out
with a whimper of weak holiday sales at department stores and car
dealerships.
   Sales totaled $1.61 trillion for the year, up 6.7 percent from
1987 and the largest annual increase since a 9.8 percent gain in
1984, the Commerce Department said Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-made car and truck sales rose 5.6 percent
during early January this year compared with the same period last
year, despite a 19.8 percent decline in car sales at General Motors
Corp.
   The drop at GM may have been due to dealers moving some sales
from early January to late December to inflate year-end numbers,
analysts speculated on Friday. Strong truck sales helped bolster
sagging automobile sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soft drink giant Pepsico Inc. has agreed to buy
General Cinema Corp.'s bottling business for $1.75 billion in cash,
the companies announced two weeks after an earlier deal fell through.
   The previous deal, which carried a price tag of $1.5 billion,
disintegrated after the Federal Trade Commission asked for
additional details to determine whether it might violate antitrust
laws. The delay prevented the sale from being completed in time for
General Cinema to obtain tax deferral benefits.
   ``We're delighted that we reached a new agreement like this,''
General Cinema spokesman Phil Nardone said Friday.
</TEXT>
