<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in modest early European trading
today, helped by persistant speculative interest, currency dealers
said. Gold prices fell.
   Traders said the market was attempting to test the resolve of the
central banks. The banks and some financial institutions are closed
for national holidays in Japan and the United States, meaning they
could not participate in any coordinated intervention.
   ``The Europeans would have to go it alone if they want to push
the dollar lower,'' said a dealer at a major West German bank in
Frankfurt.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8540 West German marks, up from 1.8275; 1.5815
Swiss francs, up from 1.5715; 6.3150 French francs, up from 6.2505;
2.0917 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0655; 1,358.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,346.50; 1.1990 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1982.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7610, cheaper for buyers
than $1.7770 Friday.
   In London, the dollar was also quoted at 127.65 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $401.65 a troy ounce,
down from $405.75 bid late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $401.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $401.65, down from $405.75 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 48 cents to close at a bid
$402.65.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.88 a troy ounce,
its lowest level since March 1987, compared with Friday's $5.96.
</TEXT>
