<HEAD>London Shares Boosted At Midday By Retail Sales Figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher, although off their best
levels, at midday Monday, boosted by British retail sales figures.
   Shares were already on an upward course during the morning,
pushed higher by strong institutional support and special situations
in a handful of stocks.
   Then the market was encouraged by news that retail sales dipped
0.1 percent in December, indicating that higher costs of borrowing
were beginning to bite into consumer demand. The market had been
expecting a 0.3-percent rise.
   In addition, traders interpreted the slip in retail sales to mean
that interest rates won't need to be hiked further to curb
inflationary pressures in the economy.
   But, the rally fizzled as players became cautious over
Wednesday's U.S. trade figures for November.
   By about 12:30 p.m., the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share
index was 11.4 points, or 0.6 percent, better at 1,873.5.
   The morning peak was 1,877.1. The index opened at its minimum
level of 1,866.6.
   Turnover amounted to a moderate 288.1 million shares, compared
with 487.8 million shares at the same time Friday.
