<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 0844EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Dumping     01-16 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Dumping,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Opens Inquiry Into Imports Of Asian Cassette Tapes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The EEC Commission said Monday it had
begun an inquiry into imports of audio cassette tapes from Asia
which are allegedly being sold in the 12-nation trade bloc at below
market prices.
   The Commission said it had opened the anti-dumping investigation
after receiving a complaint from the European Council of Chemical
Manufacturers' Federations on behalf of EEC producers of audio
cassette tapes.
   CEFIC claimed that the imports from Japan, South Korea and Hong
Kong rose 23 percent between 1984 and 1987. It said the three
countries had exported 234.5 million audio cassettes in 1987, up
from 190.6 million in 1984, taking their share of the European
Economic Community market from 65 percent to 71 percent in 1987.
   The complaint also alleges that the Asian tapes were undercutting
prices charged by EEC producers by between 3.4 percent and 28.5
percent.
   CEFIC said that as a result of this price undercutting, EEC
producers had had to lower their prices so much that they had
suffered ``substantial reduction of their profits and significant
losses.''
   EEC producers' production had dropped from 156 million audio
cassettes in 1984 to 151 million in 1987, CEFIC said.
   Among the 20 exporters from Hong Kong named in the complaint who
exported 24.2 million audio tapes in 1987, are Magnetic Enterprise
Ltd., Sound and Sound (H.K.) Magnetic Tape Ltd., and the Sun Tak
Magnetic Industrial Co.
   The nine Japanese exporters, whose exports totaled 173.2 million
tapes in 1987 are 3M, Fuji Film, TDK, Maxell, Konica, Sony, Victor,
Matsushita and Columbia.
   The six South Korean firms exported 37.1 million audio cassette
tapes in 1987. They are Sun Electronics, Inc., Goldstar@CC,VC,
SKC@VC, SK Magnetic@CC, Saehan Media@CC,VC and Kolon@VC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
