<SECOND>PM-Britain-GEC,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Expected to Join Bid for GEC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. is expected to
take part in a planned consortium bid for General Electric Co. PLC
of Britain, a respected financial daily reported Monday.
   Analysts said, however, that GEC's defenses against a consortium
takeover bid was strengthened by its announcement Friday of a merger
with the U.S.-based General Electric Co. of their European consumer
products, medical equipment and some electrical divisions.
   The Financial Times reported that AT&amp;T was expected to confirm
its participation in the dramatic bid for GEC this week following
weekend negotiations with Lazard Brothers investment firm.
   The Financial Times and other newspapers also reported that the
British electronics firm Plessey Co. PLC made a bid to acquire GPT,
an electronics company it jointly owns with GEC, citing a broken
agreement between the two companies.
   GEC, which itself has made a $3 billion bid with West Germany's
Siemens AG for Plessey, said it would fight to keep its share of
GPT, reports in The Guardian and Financial Times said.
   The financial daily said that under a deal with the consortium,
AT&amp;T would take a controlling stake in GPT. It said AT&amp;T would
announce its participation after a board meeting Wednesday in New
York.
   In the United States, AT&amp;T spokesman Walter Murphy declined to
comment on the reports.
   Lazard Brothers is the merchant bank adviser to Plessey, which
also has been reported to be a member of the consortium bidding for
GEC, along with the French company Thomson.
   The announcement of a deal between GE and GEC dampened
speculation that GE, which had not been related to the British GEC,
would participate in the consortium to buy GEC. GE is paying $580
million to GEC in the joint-venture agreement.
   In the case of GPT, Plessey served notice to GEC Saturday night
that it intended to buy out GEC's holding in the company they formed
a year ago, the reports said.
   Plessey said that GEC, by making its bid with Siemens, had broken
an agreement not to change the 50-50 ownership arrangement, the
dailies reported. GEC had promised Siemens 40 percent of Plessey.
   If either side broke the agreement, the other was allowed to buy
its share at a price determined by independent auditors.
   A spokesman for Plessey, who was not named, denied the company's
move was designed as a ``spoiling tactic. We believe they have
broken an agreement in good faith. We have to protect our
shareholders' interests,'' the Observer reported Sunday.
   But an unnamed GEC spokesman called the move a ``pretty
unconvincing argument,'' in the Financial Times.
   On Thursday, the British government referred the GEC-Siemens bid
for Plessey to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission, which blocks
the takeover during a three-month inquiry into its effects on
competition.
   The European Economic Community Commission will examine the
agreement between GE and GEC closely before deciding to investigate
whether it impedes fair competition within the 12-nation trade bloc,
according to an official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
