<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Ford     01-16 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Ford,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford to Switch Sierra Production to Belgium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. Ltd. said Monday it plans to switch
production of its Sierra model from Britain to Belgium as part of
its strategy to prepare for the single European market in 1992.
   The gradual production switch is likely to cut 500 jobs in
Dagenham, northeast of London, and create 2,000 jobs in Genk,
Belgium, over the next five years, said a Ford spokesman, who wasn't
identified, in accordance with British practice.
   Ford said it planned to achieve the job reductions through
attrition and voluntary layoffs.
   ``It's all part of a realignment of our European production
program to increase capacity and improve efficiency,'' the Ford
spokesman said. ``The basic logic behind the whole thing is that a
plant producing one type of car is more efficient than one producing
two types of cars.''
   The moves will strengthen the company's ability to meet
anticipated increases and variations in demand by 1992, when the
Common Market is to become one barrier-free marketplace of 320
million consumers, Ford said.
   Dagenham, which currently employs 8,300 auto workers, will
concentrate on the new Fiesta model, to be introduced in the spring,
with production to be increased to match the current combined output
of Sierras and Fiestas of 1,100 a day.
   Genk, which employs about 10,000 people, is to become the sole
European source for the Sierra, producing an expected 1,500 a day.
It now produces about 1,100 Sierras daily, plus Transit vans.
   Amalgamated Engineering Union executive member Jimmy Airlie,
secretary of the seven-union Ford negotiating committee, said: ``Our
initial reaction is one of considerable concern.
   ``The Sierra is Ford's most important car and the loss of
production from the U.K. will have a catastrophic effect on the
Dagenham operation. The full ramifications of the announcement are
not yet known.''
   All the unions involved are to hold an urgent meeting later this
week, Airlie said.
   Ford also has plants in Halewood, Britain; Cologne, West Germany;
and Valencia, Spain.
</TEXT>
