<DOCNO> AP890116-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RJRBuyout     01-16 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-RJR Buyout,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Holding Out Their RJR Stock</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM (AP) _ Some RJR Nabisco stockholders are refusing
to part with their RJR Nabisco stock, apparently under the belief
that their RJR dividends will keep coming in the mail, financial
officials say.
   In addition, some feel they are voting against the buyout, by not
tendering ``and that's a real mistake,'' said David Schamens,
managing executive of Integrated Resources Equity Corp.
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. won the bidding war for RJR Nabisco
six weeks ago in a record $25 billion cash deal.
   Schamens said about 2 percent of his RJR callers are holdouts.
   ``They think that the dividends are just going to keep coming in
the mail every three months, and, unfortunately, they're wrong,''
Schamens said.
   Under the law, stockholders have two years to trade their RJR
Nabisco shares for the new securities. If they take no action, their
holdings then go to a North Carolina fund where it is held for seven
years. If not claimed in that time, it belongs to the state.
   Harry Rolison, manager of corporate trust at Wachovia Bank and
Trust Co., said he talked with a couple last week who did not plan
to sell their shares on the market or tender them to KKR.
   They were planning to take securities that KKR expects to issue
for RJR stock after its cash offer expires Jan. 31. But they did not
realize they would be losing their RJR Nabisco dividend.
   ``Once they understood that, it was obvious to me that they were
reconsidering,'' Rolison said.
   KKR won the right to acquire RJR Nabisco with a bid of $25
billion. Under the terms of the cash tender offer, KKR will pay $109
a share in cash for about 74 percent of RJR Nabisco's outstanding
common stock. In a second step expected in late April or May, KKR
will issue preferred stock and converting debentures for the
remaining shares.
   When the deal is done, stockholders who tendered their shares
will have received about $81 in cash and $28 in securities for each
share.
   Gene Hoots, an investment consultant in Winston-Salem, said he
thinks there is a sizable group of stockholders who have done
nothing to get ready to sell or tender.
   ``There are people who have actually left town for extended
periods without ... having taken care of this,'' he said. ``For
those people, this could be a very expensive decision.
   ``For goodness sakes, they need to get their paperwork in order
and talk to somebody who can help them.''
   The securities KKR will issue are expected to be traded at a
discount of about 70 percent of their face value immediately after
the transaction is completed. But KKR has included a provision in
the deal that it hopes will raise the value of the securities to par
value in two years.
   While many stockholders are opting to sell their stock outright,
Schamens said he is advising people to tender their shares to KKR.
RJR Nabisco stock closed at $94.75 Friday on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
