<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0266</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today in quiet
holiday trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 1.25 to 2,227.32 by
11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 586 up, 540 down and 555
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 38.98 million shares at
midmorning.
   Trading had been expected to be light because of the absence of
many investors taking the day off in observance of the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr.'s birthday.
   Analysts said the mood of the markets kept brightening gradually
as the rally in stock prices that began last November continued into
the new year.
   By the end of last week, several primary indicators of market
trends stood at their highest levels since the crash in October 1987.
   However, brokers said some traders were selling today to cash in
on those gains. Many Wall Streeters worry that the rally cannot make
much progress unless interest rates turn downward.
   Texas Eastern led the active list and jumped 14[ to 44] on word
of Coastal Corp.'s plan to make a $42-a-share bid for the company.
   Sound Warehouse, which agreed to be acquired by Shamrock Holdings
for $25.65 a share, rose 2[ to 24[ in the over-the-counter market.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.28 to 159.86. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .70 at 316.63.
