<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1442EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SwimsuitEditions Bjt   01-16 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swimsuit Editions, Bjt,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swimsuit Issues Prove Big Mid-Winter Sellers for Sports Mags</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year ago, Sport magazine swore off swimsuit
issues, and gave its readers a pinup sports calendar rather than
``devoting 16 pages to luscious photos of beautiful women in
swimsuits'' as competing magazines did.
   ``There are no sexy pictures there (just some remarkable sports
photos), but you don't have to hide it from your kid either,'' the
magazine's editor said in a message to readers in the
January-February 1988 issue.
   But that was last year.
   Sport's latest issue recently hit the stands with a dark-haired
model on the cover, appropriately dressed for what the headline over
the magazine title called its ``Hot Swimsuit Issue.''
   The magazine's executives note that new owners _ and a new editor
_ have taken over since the last policy pronouncement on swimsuits.
Petersen Publishing Co., based in Los Angeles, bought the magazine
last summer.
   And the new owners say they are giving the predominantly-male
sports magazine audience what it wants, as demonstrated by the huge
popularity of the swimsuit issues from its rivals, Sports
Illustrated and Inside Sports.
   What's a faithful follower of Sport magazine to think?
   ``Our readers are going to be happy that Sport magazine changed
its mind,'' said executive editor Kelly Garrett.
   Sport is reviving its swimsuit issue just weeks before Sports
Illustrated celebrates the 25th anniversary of its first swimsuit
edition with a blitz that will include a pay-cable program, a home
video and a desk calendar.
   Sports Illustrated designed its initial swimsuit issue as a
travel feature to brighten up the dark days between the football and
baseball seasons when many Northern cities are snowbound and sports
fans are blue.
   The swimsuit issues periodically have sparked protests that the
sections are sexist, exploit women and are unsuited to a sports
magazine. Some readers threaten subscription cancellations, although
publisher Donald Barr said he had fewer than 50 cancellations due to
last year's swimsuit issue.
   Sports Illustrated charges about 28 percent more for ad space and
75 percent more for a single copy of its swimsuit issue. It expects
to sell nearly 5.5 million copies of this year's special issue _
which hits the newstands Feb. 6 _ compared with the usual 3 million
for regular issues.
   Barr has also agreed as part of the 25th anniversary to have a
video shot in connection with the swimsuit issue.
   Home Box Office Inc. plans to air the 47-minute video about
shooting the swimsuit issue several times starting Feb. 9. A
slightly longer home video will made available a few days later in
video, retail and magazine stores.
   Bridget Potter, an HBO executive, said retailers had placed about
350,000 orders for the home video, which will be priced at $19.99.
It will carry two automobile commercials for which Chrysler Corp.
paid $337,500.
   Next fall, a special 25th anniversary desk calendar will be
published for 1990 using photos taken for the 1989 swimsuit issue.
Tom Ettinger of Sports Illustrated Enterprises said he expects to
sell about 250,000 desk calendars at $12.95 each in addition to
500,000 of the usual wall calendars at $10.95 each.
   Magazine executives decline to say how much will be made from the
25th anniversary issue and related products, but Business Week
magazine estimates total sales could reach $30 million.
   Inside Sports, owned by Century Publishing Co. in Evanston, Ill.,
has its ninth swimsuit issue on the newsstands, and hopes to sell
850,000 copies compared with a normal rate base of 500,000.
   The magazine's first swimsuit issue was a parody of Sports
Illustrated's version, showing pretty women in swimwear carrying
rolled-up copies of the competition's swimsuit issue.
   ``It was so well-received that we decided we would keep doing our
own every year,'' said marketer Jerry Croft.
   Sport magazine tried its first swimsuit issue in March 1986,
featuring swimsuit-clad women athletes from all fields, but sales
failed to improve.
   In his message to readers last year, then-editor Neil Cohen
wrote, ``We didn't feel comfortable with the pages, they didn't fit
our magazine.''
   This year, Sport used professional models rather than athletes in
swimsuits. Publisher Lew Green is looking for a sales boost _ but
won't say how much _ in Sport's rate base of 850,000 copies.
   Green makes no apology for the change in philosophy on swimsuit
issues.
   ``What we are showing here is appropriate for a young male
audience,'' he said. ``... It's part of what sports are all about.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
