<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     01-16 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Stronger In Europe, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMer expected by 5 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose Monday against most major
currencies in European trading.
   Gold prices fell, and silver dipped to its lowest level in nearly
22 months in London.
   Foreign exchange dealers said trading activity was lighter than
normal because of holidays in the United States and Japan.
   They said that with chances reduced for market intervention by
either the U.S. or Japanese central banks, dealers tested the
dollar's strength and pushed dollar rates higher.
   Dealers said the market was looking toward Wednesday's expected
release of U.S. trade figures for November. The November deficit is
expected to widen from the October deficit of $10.35 billion.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7615 late Monday from
$1.7770 late Friday.
   Also in London, the dollar traded late in the day at 128.05
Japanese yen, compared with 126.65 yen late Friday in Tokyo.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with Friday's
late rates, included: 1.8575 West German marks, up from 1.8275;
1.5835 Swiss francs, up from 1.5715; 6.3285 French francs, up from
6.2505; 2.0965 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0655; 1,359.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,346.50; and 1.1965 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1982.
   Gold bullion prices sagged, as traders cited the stronger dollar.
   Gold fell to $401.75 a troy ounce in London and $401.35 an ounce
in Zurich, down from $405.75 an ounce in both cities late Friday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $402.65 an ounce, down from
$403.13 at the end of last week.
   Silver bullion fell to its lowest level since March 26, 1987,
trading late in London at $5.89 a troy ounce, down from $5.96 late
Friday.
</TEXT>
