<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1534EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   01-16 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans, Oats Close Limit Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most corn, soybean and oat futures prices plunged
their permitted daily limits Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade in
reaction to a government report indicating corn and soybean supplies
were larger than expected.
   Wheat futures prices closed mixed.
   Corn futures dropped to their lowest level since Dec. 21 and
soybeans hit their lowest price since Dec. 14 in reaction to an
Agriculture Department crop report released Friday after the grain
markets closed.
   The USDA said 1988 U.S. corn production totaled 4.92 billion
bushels, more than 30 percent below the 1987 harvest but much higher
than market analysts had expected.
   The USDA pegged the nation's corn stockpile as of Dec. 1 at 7.07
billion bushels, down from 9.77 billion a year earlier but still
well above pre-report estimates.
   The corn numbers were considered the most bearish in the report,
but the government's numbers for soybean production and stocks also
were greater than expected.
   The USDA's wheat numbers, taken alone, were bullish. But analysts
said the corn and soybean markets pulled down wheat prices for
near-month delivery.
   Analysts said they expected corn and soybean futures to open
lower on Tuesday.
   Corn and most oat futures contracts lost 10 cents a bushel, the
daily limit. Four of the nine soybean delivery months fell by 30
cents a bushel, the limit in that market, and the limitless contract
for January delivery fell 36} cents.
   At the close, wheat was 10{ cents lower to 3 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in March at $4.30{ a bushel; corn was 10
cents lower across the board with March at $2.78\ a bushel; oats
were 9 cents to 10 cents lower with March at $2.33 a bushel;
soybeans were 18{ cents to 36} cents lower with January at $7.67 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
