<FIRST>r f AM-Contributions     01-16 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contributions,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corporate Contributions Continue To Level Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 6:30 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contributions to worthy causes by the largest
U.S. corporations continue to level off, the Conference Board said
Monday.
   According to a survey of 328 leading corporations, contributions
rose by less than 5 percent in 1987, the latest year for which
complete data were available.
   Donations over the last three years have gone up by 3 percent to
7 percent annually. These are much smaller rises than the
double-digit ones posted over the previous decade, said the board, a
nonprofit group that does management and economic research.
   Total contributions, including those made by both large and small
corporations, came to about $4.6 billion in 1987, the same as the
1986 level.
   In 1988, corporate giving appears to have been flat or possibly
less than in 1987, the sponsors of the survey said. The survey was
jointly sponsored by the Board and the Council for Aid to Education.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
