<FIRST>r f AM-Heileman-Cleary     01-16 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heileman-Cleary,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Longtime Heileman Executive Steps Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA CROSSE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Russell G. Cleary announced Monday he is
stepping down as chairman and president of G. Heileman Brewing Co.
after 18 years to pursue private business interests.
   Australian brewing magnate Alan Bond, who purchased Heileman in
1987, will become chairman, company officials said.
   Murray S. Cutbush, 43, a Bond Corp. executive from Chicago, was
named Heileman's new president and chief operating officer, the
company said.
   Cleary, 55, said he would remain as a consultant for the brewery
but was resigning to take over a new family enterprise, Cleary
Management Corp.
   Cleary joined Heileman as legal counsel in 1960 and was named
president in 1971 after his father-in-law, the late Roy E. Kumm,
retired.
   Under Kumm and Cleary, the brewery made more than 50 acquisitions
and rose from the nation's 39th-largest brewer to fourth in national
sales by 1986. Sales increased from $100 million in 1970 to more
than $1.3 billion last year.
   Bond Corp., a multinational company headquartered in Australia,
became the world's fifth-largest brewer when it acquired Heileman.
</TEXT>
