<DOCNO> AP890116-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1816EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TexasEastern Bjt   01-16 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Eastern, Bjt,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coastal to Begin Cash Tender Offer for Texas Eastern Corp.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal Corp. announced Monday it planned to
launch a $2.6 billion tender offer for Texas Eastern Corp. in a deal
that would make Coastal the nation's largest natural gas company.
   The $42 per share offer was about 40 percent more than Texas
Eastern's closing stock price on Friday.
   The announcement sent Texas Eastern stock soaring by $14.75 a
share to $45 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange, which
analysts said indicated the bidding may go higher.
   At the same time, Coastal's stock fell 75 cents a share to
$34.12{.
   Houston-based Coastal is the third largest natural gas company in
the country while Texas Eastern, also of Houston, is among the top
six. Another Houston firm, Enron Corp., holds the top position,
analysts said.
   ``In my view, Coastal and Enron are two prototypes of interstate
pipeline networks of the future,'' said Charles Strain, director of
energy research for Lovett Mitchell Webb &amp; Garrison in Houston.
   Texas Eastern is attractive to both companies because of its
pipeline system reaching the Northeast market.
   Strain said even though the acquisition will put Coastal further
in debt, in the long run it is a good move because pipeline
regulations are expected to be relaxed.
   William D. Hyler, an analyst for Oppenheimer &amp; Co. Inc. in New
York, said he was surprised by Coastal's timing of the offer because
of its debt.
   Coastal had nearly $3.5 billion in debt outstanding as of Sept.
30, according to Coastal spokesman R.W. Wells.
   ``I believe they've always had an interest in this company,''
Hyler said. ``Apparently they thought that if they waited someone
else would get it. In the long term, it looks good. It's a good
strategic fit.''
   Hyler said if the buyout were successful, he expected Coastal to
sell off Texas Eastern's exploration and production operations.
   Monday's jump in the price of Texas Eastern stock, however,
prompted analysts to predict Coastal would have to sweeten its offer
to $45 or $48 per share.
   Texas Eastern urged its shareholders not to not to take any
action on the expected tender offer until it makes its
recommendation.
   ``When the offer is received, the board of directors of Texas
Eastern will carefully consider the offer and expects to advise its
shareholders of its recommendation no later than 10 business days
from the date of commencement of such tender offer,'' Texas Eastern
said in a statement.
   Coastal said the decision to make the offer was approved at a
Sunday night meeting of its board of directors. Coastal said it
would begin the offer on Tuesday for all outstanding shares of Texas
Eastern's common stock.
   U.S. District Judge Lynn Hughes in Houston was considering a
request from Coastal for a temporary restraining order to keep Texas
Eastern's board of directors from taking any action to prevent
shareholders from accepting the offer.
   James R. Paul, president and chief operating officer of Coastal,
wrote his counterpart at Texas Eastern, Dennis R. Hendrix,
requesting a meeting with the Texas Eastern board of directors to
discuss a business combination.
   ``We are convinced that a combination of Coastal and Texas
Eastern would be in the best interests of our respective
stockholders as well as employees, customers and suppliers,'' Paul
wrote. ``Operating flexibility and efficiencies brought about by a
combination of our companies would significantly improve the
abilitites of each company to provide the best possible service to
customers.
   ``We also believe that our offer is a fair one. It gives Texas
Eastern's stockholders an opportunity to receive immediately a very
attractive cash price for all their shares.''
   Coastal is diversified energy firm with $8 billion in assets and
operations in natural gas transmission and storage, gas and oil
exploration and production, refining and marketing, coal, trucking
and independent power production.
   Texas Eastern, with $5 billion in assets, is involved in natural
gas and petroleum products, pipeline and international oil and gas
exploration and production. It also refines and markets petroleum
products at wholesale and is involved in real estate projects.
   Coastal said its offer will be financed primarily by bank
borrowings and subordinated notes. Citibank has told the company by
letter it is confident it can provide up to $2 billion in senior
bank financing including $500 million Citibank will provide under a
firm commitment.
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. sent a letter to Coastal saying it is
confident it can place up to $1.3 billion in subordinated notes of
Coastal.
   Drexel's involvment in the takeover attempt comes at a time when
it is finalizing details of its securities fraud plea bargain
settlement with the federal government.
   Under an agreement with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Drexel agreed to pay a record $650 million in fines and restitution,
plead guilty to six unspecified felonies, settle related civil
litigation with the SEC and agree to cooperate in the government's
expanding campaign against Wall Street corruption.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890116-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1825EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-GeneralElectric Bjt   01-16 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-General Electric, Bjt,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>GE Strengthens European Foothold Ahead of 1992</HEAD>
<HEAD>Repeating for all needing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's General Electric Co. has strengthened its
European foothold ahead of 1992 by stepping into a complex
electronics industry takeover battle and emerging with an agreement
with Britain's General Electric Co. PLC to merge European operations.
   The U.S. and British companies, previously unrelated, announced
on Friday that they had reached agreement to merge their European
consumer products, medical equipment and some electrical divisions.
   American and Japanese companies are eager to expand operations in
Europe before 1992, when the 12-nation Common Market is to be
transformed into one barrier-free marketplace of 320 million people.
   GE, the U.S. company, is paying GEC $580 million to create the
joint operations, which will have annual revenue of about $2.45
billion.
   The agreement also helps GEC by serving as a defensive tactic
against a possible takeover bid for GEC by an international
consortium.
   The investment firm Lazard Brothers and Co. announced on Jan. 8
that a new company had been formed to create an international
consortium to make a bid for GEC.
   Such a bid was expected to amount to between $11 billion and $14
billion, making it Britain's largest takeover ever.
   Plessey Co., the target of a $3 billion joint takeover attempt by
GEC and West Germany's Siemens AG, was expected to participate in
the potential consortium bid to buy GEC. Such a counter-bid would be
what Wall Street calls a Pac Man defense, an allusion to the
eat-or-be-eaten video game.
   GE had been rumored to be interested in joining a bid for GEC,
but the announcement of a deal between GE and GEC cooled that
speculation.
   However, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. was expected to
confirm this week its participation in a consortium bid, the
Financial Times reported Monday. In the United States, AT&amp;T
spokesman Walter Murphy declined to comment.
   A Lazard Brothers official did not return a phone call from The
Associated Press. Lazard Brothers serves as adviser to Plessey,
which has declined comment on the consortium bid.
   GEC and Siemens' offer for Plessey, launched in November, is on
hold for three months following the British government's decision
Thursday to have the Monopolies and Mergers Commission examine its
effect on competition.
   The European Economic Community Commission also is examining the
offer.
   GE's arrangement with GEC fits a strategy followed by many
non-European companies, which are concerned that 1992 might see the
emergence of a ``Fortress Europe,'' shutting them out of the huge,
lucrative market.
   European companies also have scrambled to form pan-European
alliances.
   ``What it (GE) has done is significantly increase the size of its
business in Europe by this deal,'' said analyst Keith Sykes of the
London investment firm Smith New Court PLC. ``The prime reason is
1992.''
   He added: ``There are a number of other people who must be
feeling shut out of the market. I think there are quite a number of
people looking to position themselves. I think there's going to be
more of this.''
   However, electronics companies' efforts to expand their
businesses across borders will be hampered by governmernts' concerns
about national security and other matters, Sykes said.
   The electronics business has been largely domestic because the
companies usually do a big portion of their business with state
agencies, such as defense departments and state telecommunications
concerns, Sykes said.
   ``It's going to be really difficult but I think at least they are
going to have a go at it,'' he said.
   Analyst Chris Tucker of Kleinwort Grieveson Ltd. said the
takeover scramble has been spurred by overcrowding.
   ``There's been overcapacity in the U.K. industry and there is a
need for rationalization,'' he said.
   GE and GEC were founded independently a century ago and have
grown into the largest electronics companies in their own countries.
   GE, a minority stakeholder in GEC from 1928 until 1934, is much
larger, with annual revenue of $40.5 billion in 1987.
   GE said its European revenue, which totaled $2 billion in 1987,
should swell to an estimated $6 billion in 1989.
   It already has European interests in plastics, medical diagnostic
equipment, electrical distribution control and protection products,
and information services.
   GEC had revenue of $9.8 billion in the year ended March 31.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890116-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1828EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-16 0845</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0874</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean, Oat Futures Fall The Limit On Crop Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for future deliveries of corn, oats and soybeans plunged
their permitted daily limits Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade
after a government report showed larger supplies of corn and
soybeans than most experts had expected.
   On other markets, livestock and meat futures declined; energy
futures surged; copper was sharply higher; precious metals were
mixed; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Wheat settled 10\ cents lower to 3 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in March at $4.30} a bushel; corn was 10 cents lower
across the board with March at $2.78\ a bushel; oats were 9 cents to
10 cents lower with March at $2.33 a bushel; and soybeans were 19
cents to 37 cents lower with January at $7.66} a bushel.
   The Chicago Board of Trade limits corn and oat futures to daily
moves of 10 cents a bushel, wheat to 20 cents a bushel and soybeans
to 30 cents a bushel. The limit on the January soybean contract has
been lifted pending the contract's pending expiration.
   Analysts said they had expected the sharp declines, especially in
the corn market, in reaction to an Agriculture Department crop
report released after the close of trading on Friday.
   The report's final 1988 U.S. corn production figure _ 4.92
billion bushels _ was nearly 6 percent higher than the average
pre-report estimate of market analysts and more than 5 percent above
the USDA's last projection, which it made in November.
   The USDA pegged the nation's corn stockpile as of Dec. 1 at 7.07
billion bushels, more than 6 percent higher than the average
pre-report estimate.
   The government's numbers for soybean production and soybean
stocks also were higher than expected.
   The USDA's wheat numbers were considered bullish but analysts
said the corn and soybean markets pulled down wheat prices for
near-month delivery.
   The sharp drop in prices may force some corn producers to
reconsider their strategies for the new growing season, said Cathy
Leow, a grain-market analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.
in New York.
   She said corn's recent rise to levels near $2.80 a bushel may
have prompted some farmers to consider dropping out of the
government's price-support program, in which they agree to limit
their corn acreage in return for a guaranteed selling price.
   But now, she said, ``I think a lot of them will think twice about
dropping out of the program, given current price levels. It will
affect planting decisions but we don't know how much.''
   The soybean market came under additional pressure Monday from
reports of weekend showers in the South American soybean belt,
analysts said.
   Under exchange rules, the daily price limit for corn futures will
be expanded Tuesday to 15 cents a bushel, but analysts said they did
not expect a second session of limit losses.
   Most livestock and meat futures prices fell on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange on expectations of lower feed costs in the
future, analysts said. Sharply lower cash prices for hogs added to
the selling pressure.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent to .35 cent lower with February at
74.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .20 cent
higher with January at 84.80 cents a pound; live hogs were .52 cent
to .93 cent lower with February at 44.87 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .10 cent to .68 cent lower with February at 42.05 cents
a pound.
   Copper futures soared on New York's Commodity Exchange on reports
that repairs to an explosion-damaged flash furnace at the Chilean
Copper Corp.'s Chuquicamata mine could take two months.
   Chile is the world's largest copper exporter and the Chuquicamata
mine is the world's largest copper mine, accounting for more than
half of Chile's annual copper output, said Craig Sloane, an analyst
in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   ``The market is balanced finely enough that if you can affect
production in Chile from this mine for a couple of months, that's
significant,'' he said.
   Copper settled 2.80 cents to 4.45 cents higher with March at
$1.4805 a pound.
   Gold settled 10 cents to 30 cents lower on the Commodity Exchange
with February at $403.30 a troy ounce; silver was unchanged to 0.2
cent higher with March at $5.957 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures surged on the New York Mercantile Exchange to
their highest levels since November 1987 on perceptions that the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries was succeeding in
reducing its crude-oil production, analysts said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents to 40 cents
higher with February at $18.88 a barrel; heating oil was .21 cent to
.49 cent higher with February at 53.16 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .05 cent lower to .94 cent higher with February at
50.91 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures gained modestly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of stocks
represented by the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled .40 point
higher at 286.70. Each point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
