<FIRST>r f AM-Knight-RidderPromotion     01-16 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Knight-Ridder Promotion,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buckner Names Vice President-News For Knight-Ridder Inc.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jennie Buckner, managing editor-afternoon for the
San Jose (Calif.) Mercury News, has been promoted to vice
president-news for Knight-Ridder Inc., the company announced Monday.
   The appointment, announced by P. Anthony Ridder, president of
Knight-Ridder's newspaper division, is effective July 1.
   Buckner will assume the news-editorial responsibility for
Knight-Ridder's larger newspapers and will be on the Knight-Ridder
Operating Committee. She also will be responsible for operations of
the Knight-Ridder Washington bureau.
   Buckner, 41, joined the Mercury News as features editor in 1978
after nine years at the Detroit Free Press. She became assistant
managing editor-features in 1981 and assistant managing editor-news
in 1982. She became managing editor-afternoon in 1983 and is
responsible for the news operation of the afternoon and evening
editions of the Mercury News, as well as all feature operations of
the newspaper.
   James K. Batten, Knight-Ridder president and chief operating
officer, said Buckner ``brings a strong blend of wisdom, experience
and leadership for our news operation.''
   Buckner, a graduate with honors from the Ohio State University
School of Journalism, is a member of the board of the California
Society of Newspaper Editors and of New Direction for News, an
industry organization dedicated to modernizing the content of
newspapers.
   Knight-Ridder owns 30 newspapers as well as business information
services and cable television operations. Last October, the company
announced it intends to sell its eight television stations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
