<DOCNO> AP890116-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 2050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Brazil-Debt     01-16 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Debt,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Calls Debt Interest Payments Unbearable for Latin
Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil must lower its debt interest
payments to avoid potentially serious social and political unrest,
which could stimulate calls for another debt moratorium, a top
government official said Monday.
   Finance Minister Mailson da Nobrega called ``unbearable'' the
present situation of Brazil and other Latin debtors whose massive
foreign debt payments make them net exporters of capital.
   Last year, Brazil spent $12 billion in interest payments on the
$115 billion foreign debt.
   Da Nobrega said this year Brazil must import capital and recover
economic growth to ``avoid serious problems in the social and
political fields.''
   According to da Nobrega, the debt is not Brazil's principal
problem but it is ``the principal flag waved by populist
politicians,'' who could take advantage of this presidential
election year in Brazil to push for a moratorium on interest
payments.
   In the past, some politicians have argued the $1 billion monthly
payments takes money away from needed investments in domestic social
programs.
   ``If a populist reaches the government after an electoral
campaign based on threats to foriegn creditors, there will be a
moratorium on all payments and it will be of the worst kind,'' da
Nobrega told a news conference.
   Da Nobrega said the Brazilian government, which Sunday announed a
package of economic measures including a wage and price freeze and
massive spending cuts, ``had no intention of returning to its
previous confrontational approach of dealing with foreign
creditors.''
   However, he said should the country suffer a dip in money
reserves from the measures, which included a freeing of currency
exchange and import restrictions of certain products, Brazil could
''suspend payments in common accord with creditors.''
   Last year Brazil's current account trade surplus was a record $18
billion. Brazil takes its foreign debt payments from the monthly
surplus.
   In 1987, Brazil declared an 11-month moratorium on about $70
billion of its foreign debt with private creditors saying the
country was broke, with monthly trade surpluses as low as $131
million. In return, private banks cut the country's short term
credit lines and stalled rescheduling negotiations.
   But last year Brazil eased its hard-line stand, suspended the
moratorium and reached an agreement with banks to reschedule some
$64 billion in interest and principal due over 20 years with an
eight-year grace period. They also were to receive $5.2 billion in
new financing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
