<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru   01-16 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0180,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Stronger In Quiet Market, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf, Silver prices ... to CORRECT silver's direction
to a rise sted decline in New York.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened against all key
currencies in quiet holiday trading Monday.
   Gold and silver prices fell, with silver dipping to its lowest
level in nearly 22 months in London.
   Bruce Giammattei, a currency trader for Harris Trust &amp; Co. in
Chicago, said near-term sentiment toward the dollar remained
somewhat bullish.
   ``I think there's a growing feeling in the market that the United
States doesn't really mind seeing a higher dollar at this time,''
Giammattei explained. ``A higher dollar helps take inflationary
pressure off of us by making imports cheaper.
   ``Right now the No. 1 goal in this country is to see that
inflation doesn't get out of hand.''
   Traders said the dollar also was boosted by reduced chances for
central-bank intervention from the United States and Japan due to
holidays there.
   Many U.S. traders were absent from the market Monday in
observance of the Rev. Martin Luther King's birthday, a federal
holiday. Government agencies and most banks were closed.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7615 late Monday from
$1.7770 Friday. Sterling fetched $1.7610 in New York, down from
$1.7660 on Friday.
   The dollar rose in London to 128.05 Japanese yen from 126.65 yen
Friday in Tokyo. Later, in New York, the dollar rose to 128.10 yen
from 127.30 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday's late
rates, included: 1.8565 West German marks, up from 1.8445; 1.5845
Swiss francs, up from 1.5740; 1.19785 Canadian dollars, up from
1.19775; 6.3245 French francs, up from 6.2850; and 1,352.625 Italian
lire, up from 1,352.60.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's rates,
included: 1.8575 West German marks, up from 1.8275; 1.5835 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5715; 6.3285 French francs, up from 6.2505; 2.0965
Dutch guilders, up from 2.0655; 1.1965 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1982; and 1,359.50 Italian lire, up from 1,346.50.
   Meanwhile, prices of precious metals sagged Monday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $402.20 a troy ounce from $402.30 Friday. Later,
Republic National Bank in New York quoted gold bullion at a bid of
$401.80 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $402.30 late Friday.
   Gold fell to $401.75 a troy ounce in London and to $401.35 an
ounce in Zurich, down from $405.75 an ounce in both cities late
Friday. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $402.65 an ounce, down
from $403.13 Friday.
   Silver prices rose in New York after falling in London. On New
York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose to $5.890 a
troy ounce from $5.888 Friday. In London, silver bullion fell to its
lowest level since March 26, 1987, trading at $5.89 a troy ounce,
down from $5.96 late Friday.
</TEXT>
