<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1905EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-NationalSemiconductor 2ndLd-Writethru   01-16 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-National Semiconductor, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Announces Plan To Lay Off 2,000; Will Take Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf to give full name of Mary Coady on first reference.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Semiconductor Corp. announced
plans Monday to lay off about 2,000 workers, or 5 percent of its
worldwide workforce, to cope with sluggish business.
   The Silicon Valley chip maker also said it would take a charge
against earnings in the current quarter to cover costs of the
dismissals, but said it had not yet decided how big the charge would
be.
   The stock closed unchanged at $9 a share in consolidated New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   ``This step is necessary to staff our organization around the
needs of our fundamental semiconductor business and bring our costs
into alignment with our current and projected revenues,'' Charles
Sporck, the president and chief executive, said in a statement.
   In the latest fiscal quarter ended Nov. 28, National
Semiconductor had a loss of $25 million on revenue of $705 million,
a drop from profits of $11.6 million on revenue of $640 million in
the same period a year earlier.
   National Semiconductor, which makes a broad range of integrated
circuits, has been hurt worse than some other chip makers because of
its reliance on the sluggish personal computer market. It has been
selling off unrelated units in order to focus on its core business
of semiconductors.
   It has agreed to sell its Datachecker unit to ICL, a British
company, and is selling half of its mainframe computer marketing
subsidiary, National Advanced Systems, to Memorex Telex NV of the
Netherlands.
   Datachecker, with 2,000 employees, and National Advanced Systems,
with 2,200, are exempted from the layoffs because they are being
sold. All the cuts will come from the semiconductor business and
corporate staff.
   The layoffs will occur at all levels in Asia, Europe and the
United States, with about 50 percent of the cuts taking place in the
United States, spokeswoman Mary Coady said.
   Sporck said officials expect slow growth during the current
calendar year, but are optimistic the company will maintain its
growth and long-term health.
   Last August, it announced it would take an $18 million charge for
restructuring of its Information Systems Group and lay off about 450
people. At the time, National said its business was being hurt by
slow demand and pricing pressures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
