<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 1952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ADM-IllinoisCentral     01-16 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ADM-Illinois Central,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>ADM Buys 8 Percent Stake In Illinois Central</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain processor Archer Daniels Midland Co. said
Monday it had purchased an 8 percent stake in Illinois Central
Transportation Co., a major rail hauler of grain between Chicago and
the Gulf of Mexico.
   ADM, based in Decatur, Ill., said the purchase was an investment,
not a takeover move, and industry analysts agreed.
   ``I think at this time they really are buying for investment
purposes,'' said analyst Leonard Teitlebaum of Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc. in New York. ``I don't think they have any interest in
running the railroad.''
   Illinois Central spokesman Joseph Fidanza said he knew nothing
more about ADM's intentions than what ADM had told the railroad
company.
   ``They said to us that it's for investment purposes,'' he said.
   ADM spokesman Richard Burket said the company recently purchased
the nearly 1.6 million shares of Illinois Central at market prices,
which have ranged from $12.12{ on Jan. 3, the stock's first day of
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, to $14.12{.
   Illinois Central closed Monday in composite trading at $14, 12{
cents below Friday's close, making ADM's stake worth about $22.4
million.
   Chicago-based Illinois Central became an independent company late
last year when it was spun off from its parent, IC Industries Inc.
IC then changed its own name to Whitman Corp.
   The railroad benefited from last summer's drought, which lowered
the level of the Mississippi River and forced grain companies to
ship by rail instead of by barge.
   A recent study commissioned by Illinois Central found a trend
toward drier weather in the Mississippi River watershed, prompting
projections by the railroad for continued river-shipping problems.
   Burket said he didn't know if the railroad's predictions played a
part in ADM's decision to invest in Illinois Central.
   ``As you know, the company is just available now as a railroad,''
he said, referring to the spinoff. ``We took a look at it and
decided we'd make an investment.''
   He said the stock was part of ADM's $1.2 billion portfolio of
cash and securities.
   Analyst George S. Dahlman of Piper Jaffray &amp; Hopwood Inc. in
Minneapolis said he wouldn't be surprised to see an ADM
representative named to Illinois Central's board of directors.
   ``ADM is one of the major users of railways and so I think they
know a good one when they see one,'' he said. ``I would not be
surprised to see the investment go higher, but I'd be surprised if
they tendered for the whole thing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
