<SECOND>BC-McDonnell-China,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Airline to Buy 5 MD-11 Jets for $500 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China Eastern Airlines will buy five
McDonnell Douglas MD-11 jumbo jets for a total of $500 million, the
airplane maker announced.
   The planes, four of them set up to carry passengers and one to
carry freight, are scheduled for delivery between July 1990 and
1993, McDonnell Douglas Corp. announced Monday.
   The $500 million value placed on the transaction by the
manufacturer includes spare parts and training for the crews of the
airline, one of two which flies overseas from the People's Republic
of China.
   The MD-11, successor to the company's DC-10, is being assembled
at Douglas Aircraft Co. in Long Beach, a subsidiary of St.
Louis-based McDonnell Douglas. Deliveries of the 250 planes
presently on order are set to begin in 1990.
