<DOCNO> AP890116-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 2309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Airliners 1stLd-Writethru f0270 01-16 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Airliners, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0270,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Two More Boeing 757s Found With Crossed Wires</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout with Boeing comment; No pickup; Also moved
on general newswires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more Boeing 757 jetliners have been found with
crossed wires leading to cargo hold fire extinguisher bottles,
bringing the total to five since compulsory checks began Friday, The
Times of London reported Tuesday.
   The newspaper said checks by engineers in the Netherlands and
Canada revealed that two aircraft, both less than a year old, were
wrongly wired at the Boeing plant in Seattle in the United States
before delivery.
   Boeing spokesman Tom Cole in Seattle said such problems can take
place in the manufacture or in the maintenance of airplanes.
   ``We're aware of the Air Holland findings and this does make five
airplanes reported so far,'' Cole said Monday night. ``We are
looking into the technical aspects of it to see what the miswiring
was or is, how they relate to each other, and what might have
happened so we can correct it.''
   Britain's Civil Aviation Authority reported Sunday that engineers
of the British airline Air 2000 found crossed wires during checks of
cargo compartment warning systems following the discovery of wiring
problems in two Boeing 757s in the United States since compulsory
checks began.
   Faulty wiring is one possibility being examined by experts
investigating the British Midlands Boeing 737 crash at Kegworth in
central England on Jan. 7 in which 44 people were killed.
   But The Times said the faults involving wiring to the cargo hold
fire extinguisher bottles found on the five 757s are not thought to
have been a factor in the crash of the 737 on Jan. 7.
   In the Jan. 7 crash, for some reason so far unexplained, the
right-hand engine was shut down though it was the left-hand engine
that caught fire.
   The Times said the faults in each of these two new cases were
identical to the fault discovered on a Boeing 757 operated by Air
2000.
   The CAA said Sunday that the fault on the Air 2000 plane was
caused by switched plugs and was immediately rectified.
   The Times said Tuesday that the Air 2000 plane and the two latest
planes found to have crossed wires were delivered within days of
each other.
   It said Boeing executives are now trying to trace the fitter
responsible, though Cole on Monday said Boeing was not pointing the
finger at any one person.
   Cole confirmed that the last three planes reported with problems
were manufactured at about the same time, but the first two were not.
   The Times reported: ``A 757 belonging to Air Holland was found to
have its wires crossed in checks ordered by the FAA (the U.S.
Federal Aviation Administration) following two similar faults
reported (in the United States) on a Delta Airlines 757 and another
belonging to Royal Brunei Airlines. Although the faults were not
identical they all involved the wiring to fire extinguisher bottles
in the cargo hold.''
   It did not name the Canadian charter airline that owned the other
faultily wired aircraft.
   The paper said the findings indicated that someone in Boeing's
plant at Renton, Wash., where the 757s are manufactured made
repeated errors in fitting wiring.
   ``The assembly lines for the 737 _ the type involved in the
British Midlands crash _ run alongside the 757 lines and efforts are
now being made to ensure that similar mistakes were not made,'' the
paper said.
   Cole said: ``The Boeing Company will examine what's happened and
study the way the bottles are put in there. We'll see if something
can be done to make them less fallible.
   ``We do have a large number of checks and balances before we send
these out and that's why we want to study these'' reports, he added.
   Cole said Boeing didn't yet know whether the wiring problems were
identical, although all affect the cargo fire suppression system.
That system has nothing to do with engines, he said.
   An FAA directive that all American airlines check their 757s for
the problem is to conclude Tuesday afternoon, Cole said, at which
time it will be announced whether the problem is more widespread.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
